{ Welcome to the course!  The aim of this course is to provide you with a strong and practical repertoire against the French defense. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3
{ The 3. Bd3 variation has a lot less theory than the 3.Nc3 Winawer/Classical or the 3.Nd2 Tarrasch variations. Nonetheless, it still poses Black several problems and there are only a handful of lines where he can equalize.   I have tried to remain as objective as possible in this repertoire and have clearly pointed out the lines in which Black is able to equalize. I believe that searching for the best moves for both sides is key when preparing an effective opening repertoire. My hope is that this repertoire is also useful for French defense players with the black pieces. Notwithstanding, even when the final position is objectively equal, I have strived to propose continuations where White can pose some practical problems. After thorough analysis, I have found that Black has to be aware of several subtleties and be much more precise than I initially thought in order to equalize. A single misstep in one of the critical variations and Black can easily land in a much worse position.  3. Bd3 has been played by several top players including Magnus Carlsen, Vladimir Kramnik, and Maxime Vachier-Lagrave so you will be in good company. One of the main exponents of this variation is the 2600+ GM Vladimir Onischuk who has won an immense amount of games with 3. Bd3  (several of which against strong GMs)  .  I have divided the material into 7 theoretical chapters:    Sidelines on move two such as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  2...c5  ,  2...a6  and  2...b6  are covered in chapter 1.   The unusual  3...Nc6  is covered inchapter 2.   3...Nf6  has been played quite a lot but does not equalize. It is coveredin chapter 3.   3...c5  aiming to transpose to a variation of the Exchange French is coveredin chapter 4. }
3... dxe4
{ We devote three chapters to 3...dxe4, which is the most common move. The 5th, 6th and 7th move alternatives are covered inchapter 5. Alternatives on move 9 are examined inchapter 6. Finally, we devote the entirety ofchapter 7 to the main line with 9...a6, which is Black's most testing option against 3. Bd3.  Several model games that illustrate key ideas and plans are annotated inchapter 8. Finally, I also included some tactical puzzles from games in this variation inchapter 9.  I hope you enjoy this course and score a lot of points with 3. Bd3!  If you have any questions, do not hesitate to ask them in the forum. I have committed to a high level of support and will gladly answer any questions you have; add or further analyze any variations you deem relevant. }
*

