[Result "*"]

{ In this informational line, I'm going to explain the main ideas of the move 3. Bd3. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4
{ A major advantage of refraining from developing the Nb1 is that after   3...Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.Ne2  c5  6.c3  White is able to strengthen the center with the c3 pawn. This effectively prevents Black from putting sufficient pressure on the d4 pawn and actually makes 3...Nf6 a dubious response to 3. Bd3.  This extra flexibility given by holding back the development of the Nb1 is also useful in certain lines of the 3...c5 variation, where the knight can also come out to a3. }
4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
{ This position is reminiscent of the Rubinstein variation of the French Defense. In the Rubinstein, Black usually develops his light-squared bishop along the b7/c6-h1 diagonal, either by b6+Bb7 or Bd7-c6.     By placing our bishop on f3, we prevent said developing scheme. The bishop is very active on f3, takes control over the e4 square, and is constantly putting pressure on the b7 pawn. This is the main idea of the 3. Bd3 variation.    As with any chess move, it also has its drawbacks. The most obvious one is that the Ng1 now cannot occupy the f3 square. However, it will still be well placed on e2 and will often end up on d4 after Black plays ...c5 and ...cxd4. }
