{ I decided to list the repertoire books and databases that recommended the French Defense for Black and hyperlinks to my preferred way of tackling their recommendations vs 3. Bd3. I will try to keep this list as up to date as possible. If there is a specific repertoire book/database recommendation that I missed and that you think I should address, please post in the forum and I'll update this informational line. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4
{ 3...c5  4.exd5  exd5  5.Nf3  Nf6  6.c3  c4  was recommended in the Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: the French Defense by GM Anish Giri. I address his suggestion in the4...exd5 #7 variation.   6...Nc6  was proposed by GM Mihail Marin in a French Defense repertoire database for modern-chess.com. I tackle his recommendation in the4...exd5 #6 variation. }
4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
{ 5...Nbd7  6.Nc3  Bd6  7.Nb5  Bb4  c3  8.a6  was recommended by GM Dmitry Kryakvin in the book 'The Modern French Defence'. I address it in5...Nbd7 #5 variation. }
5... c5 6. Ne2 Nc6
{ 6...Be7  7.Nbc3  O-O  8.Be3  Qa5  was recommended in the book 'The Modern French Defence' by GM Dmitry Kryakvin. Check out the6...Be7 #3 variation for the details. }
7. Be3 cxd4
{ 7...e5  was recommended by IM John Watson in the book Play the French. Seechapter 5 for detailed analysis. }
8. Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3 Nxf3+
{ was recommended in the Play the French video series by GM Romain Edouard for chess24. This continuation is analyzed inchapter 7.   9...Bb4  was recommended by NM Bryan Tillis and GM Alex Lenderman in the Chessable course Master the French Defense. It's examined inchapter 6.   9...Be7  was recommended by GM Emanuel Berg in the GM Repertoire on the French Defense Vol. 3. It was also recommended by GM Robert Hungaski in a French Defense video series for chesslecture.com. This variation is tackled inchapter 6.   9...a6  was recommended by IM Langrock in his book/Chessable course French Defense: The Solid Rubinstein Variation. This is dealt with inchapter 7. }
