[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ Let's start with some early deviations, that is lines where Black does not go for 2...d5 and instead chooses 2...c5, 2...b6, or 2...a6. These moves are justifiably rare as White can get a sizeable advantage. As such, I see no need to remember a lot of lines, so I'll cover the most popular continuations and describe the setup White should aim for. }
2... c5
{ The most popular alternative to 2...d5 but not a particularly good one. } 3.
d5
{ This is White's best move, gaining a lot of space.  If you're an Open Sicilian player, then you can play   3.Nf3  Nevertheless, I prefer punishing such a bad move and would still encourage these players to go 3. d5. }
3... exd5 4. exd5 d6 5. c4
{ We've reached a Benoni-type structure. However, there is one key difference greatly in White's favor.   Contrary to the Modern Benoni, which arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  e6  4.Nc3  exd5  5.cxd5  we have a c-pawn and no e-pawn. Black's main counterplay in the Benoni comes from expanding on the queenside with ...a6 +...b5, which is very hard to achieve here because we have a pawn on c4.   We should also compare this position with the Old Benoni, which occurs after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  c5  2.d5  e6  Here it's well known that White should play  3.Nc3  instead of  3.c4  .  The reason is that the knight on c3 supports e2-e4 and by not playing c4, White can maneuver his g1 knight to c4 with Nf3-d2-c4. The knight is ideally placed here, controlling the e5 square and pressuring the d6 pawn.  Now note that in our current position, there is no e-pawn. This makes a world of difference! Nc3  (to support e4)  now becomes less important and it's better to play c4  (than keep the pawn on c2)  as this completely nullifies Black's b5 break. Black's other main plan in the Benoni, targeting our e-pawn is also unavailable because there isn't one here!    As such, Black's position is very suspect.   Finally, why did we start with c4 instead of Nf3? A key concept in the Benoni is to play against Black's light-squared bishop. As such, we'll first play Nc3, Bd3, and h2-h3 before playing Nf3. If we went Nf3 right away, Black would be able to pin this knight with ...Bg4 and exchange it off if necessary. Note that Black is cramped so exchanging off pieces is very helpful for him. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Be7
{ Fianchettoing the bishop with  6...g6  leaves the d6 pawn unprotected, which we can immediately target with  7.Bf4  Bg7  and now  8.Qe2+  completely disrupts Black's development.  8...Kf8  Note that   8...Qe7  9.Bxd6+−  drops the d6 pawn.  9.Qd2!  so as to avoid trading queens if Black goes ...Qe7.  9...Qe7+  10.Be2±  followed by Nf3 and O-O gives White a clear advantage. Black's king on f8 makes quite an impression. }
7. Bd3 { Taking control over the f5 square. } 7... O-O 8. h3
{ We've now stopped ...Bg4 and are finally ready to develop the knight with Nf3 on the next turn }
8... Na6
{ A common maneuver in this structure, Black redeploys the knight to c7 to support the ...b7-b5 break. }
9. Nf3 Nc7 10. O-O a6 11. a4
{ Putting an end to Black's counterplay on the queenside. With pawns on a4 and c4, achieving the ...b5 break under good conditions is nothing short of a pipe dream. }
11... b6 12. Re1
{ followed by Bf4/g5 and Qc2 gives White a clear advantage. Black's position is very cramped and he has no active plan. }
