[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ Let's start with some early deviations, that is lines where Black does not go for 2...d5 and instead chooses 2...c5, 2...b6 or 2...a6. These moves are justifiably rare as White can get a sizeable advantage. As such, I see no need to remember a lot of lines, so I'll cover the most popular continuations and describe the setup White should aim for. }
2... b6 3. Bd3 { Covering the e4 pawn in anticipation of } 3... Bb7 4. Qe2
{ I quite like developing the queen right away and find it to be the most practical route towards a clear advantage.   4.Nf3  and 4. Nc3 also lead to a big advantage. }
4... d5
{ Worse is  4...d6  5.Nf3  Nd7  6.c4  Taking over the entire center.  6...g6  7.Nc3  Bg7  8.Be3  Ne7  The so-called Hippo system. As GM Sam Shankland famously said, openings named after animals are usually terrible. This is no exception.  9.Qd2  Hinting at Bh6.  9...h6  10.O-O-O±  gave White a clear edge in the game Timman, J @@StartBracket@@2655@@EndBracket@@-Spassky, B @@StartBracket@@2625@@EndBracket@@ Hamburg 1982.   4...Nf6  is covered in my FREE course Beating ...b6 defenses. White should continue with  5.Nf3  d5   5...c5  is strongly met by  6.d5!  although  6.c3±  is simpler and still very effective.  6.e5  Nfd7  7.c4±  with full control of the center. }
5. exd5
{ We now see the point behind 4. Qe2. Black is unable to recapture with the e-pawn due to pin and consequently loses control of the center. }
5... Bxd5
{ The alternative recapture  5...Qxd5  can be answered with  6.Nf3  Nf6  7.a3  preventing ...Bb4 so as to hit Black's queen with Nc3 next.  7...Be7  8.Nc3  Qh5  now attacking the c7 pawn with  9.Bf4±  is annoying for Black to meet. O-O-O is next on the agenda. }
6. Nf3 Nf6 7. O-O Nc6
{ The natural developing move  7...Be7  is strongly met by  8.c4  sending Black's bishop packing  8...Bb7  9.Nc3  O-O  10.Re1±  followed by Bf4-e5 and Rad1 with a clear advantage. White has more space and full control over the center. }
8. c3 { Stopping any ...Nb4 shenanigans. } 8... Bd6
{ This position occurred in the engine game Needle 0.531 - Aldebaran 0.7.0 2011. An improvement is }
9. Nbd2 { heading to c4. } 9... O-O 10. Nc4 Qe7 11. Re1
{ followed by Bg5 and Nxd6 not only gives White the bishop pair but also a clear advantage. }
