[Round "?"]
[White "1. 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4
{ Let's start with some early deviations, that is lines where Black does not go for 2...d5 and instead chooses 2...c5, 2...b6 or 2...a6. These moves are justifiably rare as White can get a sizeable advantage. As such, I see no need to remember a lot of lines, so I'll cover the most popular continuations and describe the setup White should aim for. }
2... a6 { Another subpar and rare move. } 3. Bd3 d5
{ 3...b5?!  is very weakening. White is clearly better after  4.Nf3  c5  5.c3  Bb7  6.O-O±  with full control of the center. We can look to undermine Black's queenside with a2-a4 in a future. }
4. Nc3 Bb4
{ Black develops in Winawer fashion. The move ...a6 is essentially a lost tempo and allowed us to develop the bishop on d3 for free.   4...c5  can be met with  5.dxc5  Bxc5  6.exd5  exd5  And now  7.Nxd5  leads to a favorable endgame after the following forced sequence  7...Bxf2+  8.Kxf2  Qxd5  9.Qf3  Qd4+  10.Qe3+  Qxe3+  11.Bxe3⩲  White is ahead in development and has the pair of bishops, which is a big asset in this endgame. }
5. exd5 { I found this to be the simplest route towards a sizeable advantage. }
5... exd5 6. Nf3 Nf6
{ Black does not have time for  6...Bg4  as after  7.O-O±  we're ready to go Re1+. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Bg5
{ We're fully developed and threatening to win the d5 pawn @@StartBracket@@or ruin Black's kingside pawn structure@@EndBracket@@ with Bxf6. Black's bishop on b4 is completely misplaced. }
8... Be7
{ 8...Bg4?  drops the d5 pawn to  9.Bxf6  Qxf6  10.Nxd5+−   8...Be6  can be met with  9.Ne2±  with the idea Nf4.   8...Bxc3  surrenders the bishop pair  9.bxc3  Nc6  10.Re1±  is very pleasant. }
9. Re1 { Activating the rook and threatening Rxe7 followed by Nxd5. } 9... h6
10. Bh4 Nc6 11. Qd2
{ is very pleasant. We can look to reroute the knight on c3 to f5 next. } *

