[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. 3...Nc6"]
[Black "3...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nc6
{ This move is both unusual and suspect. The c7-c5 push is a very typical break in the French that enables Black to challenge White's center. Here, the knight on c6 is just in the way. That being said, it has been tried by a couple of GMs and so White should know what to do. }
4. Nf3
{ 4. c3 is more common, but the text is more flexible. The point is that f3 is the best square for the knight on g1, so White should start with this move. Depending on Black's play, White can then decide whether it's advantageous to include c3 &#x28or not&#41. We'll see that White will end up at the very minimum with a slightly better position. }
4... dxe4 5. Bxe4 Nf6 6. Bg5
{ White develops the bishop to its most active square, pinning the Nf6 and parrying the threat on the bishop on e4. We are not afraid to give up the dark squared bishop for the f6 knight. Even though Black would get the bishop pair in this case, they hardly have any prospects. The c8 bishop is blocked by the e6 pawn and the typical Rubinstein-esque development with b6+Bb7 won't be possible due to White's strong Be4. }
6... Be7 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. c3
{ White places his pawns on dark squares to limit the f6 bishop. This is a typical strategic concept: place the pawns on the opposite color of your bishop. }
8... O-O 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. O-O Bd7
{ The immediate   10...e5  pawn break would be met by  11.Bxc6  ruining Black's queenside pawn structure. }
11. Re1 { Stopping e5. } 11... e5 { This just drops a pawn. } 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13.
dxe5 Bg5 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Ne4
{ White is a clean pawn up, has two very strong knights in the center of the board, and can follow up with natural moves like Qd3 and Rad1. Black is clearly worse.    Note that Black cannot capture the e5 pawn with   15...Rxe5  as this drops a piece to  16.Nf3  forking the bishop on g5 and the rook on e5.  16...Rf5  17.Nfxg5  Rxg5  18.Nxg5  Qxg5  19.Qxd7+−  White is up a rook. }
*

