1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nc6
{ This move is both unusual and suspect. The c7-c5 push is a very typical break in the French that enables Black to challenge White's center. Here, the knight on c6 is just in the way. That being said it has been tried by a couple of GMs so White should know what to do. }
4. Nf3
{ 4. c3 is more common but the text is stronger. White will end up at the very minimum with a slightly better position. }
4... dxe4 5. Bxe4 Nf6 6. Bg5
{ White develops the bishop to its most active square, pinning the Nf6 and parrying the threat on the bishop on e4. We are not afraid to give up the dark squared bishop for the f6 knight. Even though Black would get the bishop pair in this case, they hardly have any prospects. The c8 bishop is blocked by the e6 pawn and the typical Rubinstein-esque development with b6+Bb7 won't be possible due to White's strong Be4. }
6... Be7 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. c3
{ White places his pawn on the dark-squares to limit the f6 bishop. This is a typical strategic concept: place the pawns on the opposite color of your bishop. }
8... O-O 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. O-O Bd7
{ 10...e5  11.Bxc6  ruining Black's queenside pawn structure. } 11. Re1
{ Stopping e5. } 11... h6 12. Nc4
{ White is clearly better in this position since Black can't achieve the e5 break. All of White's pieces are superior to their counterparts. White will follow up with Qd3 to connect the rooks and can then gain space on the queenside with a4 and b4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. 3...Nc6"]
[Black "3...Nc6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nc6
{ This move is both unusual and suspect. The c7-c5 push is a very typical break in the French that enables Black to challenge White's center. Here, the knight on c6 is just in the way. That being said it has been tried by a couple of GMs so White should know what to do. }
4. Nf3
{ 4. c3 is more common but the text is stronger. White will end up at the very minimum with a slightly better position. }
4... Nb4
{ Black is going after White's bishop pair but moving the knight twice in the opening is not recommended. White should simply ignore it and continue his development. Surprisingly, this move was tried by both GM Ali Marandi and GM Nazar Firman. }
5. Nc3 Nxd3+ 6. Qxd3 dxe4 7. Nxe4
{ White has a big advantage in development. Black's pair of bishops are not impressive  (especially the one on c8)  . }
7... Nf6 8. Bg5 Be7
{ We have been following the game Andriasian,Z  (2603)  -Ali Marandi,C  (2552)  Saint Louis 2018. White played 9. Bxf6 and after 9... gxf6, Black was not worse and the game ended in a draw. Much better was to capture on f6 with the knight: }
9. Nxf6+ { This capture lands White in a clearly better position. } 9... Bxf6
{ 9...gxf6  now makes no sense since White still has his dark-squared bishop.  10.Bh6±  Threatening Bg7 and Qxh7. Black's kingside pawn structure is ruined, and he still hasn't solved the problem of the c8 bishop. White is clearly better. }
10. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ After all of these recaptures, White ended up with the dream scenario of a knight vs the bad light squared French bishop. These are the kinds of positions that give French players nightmares! }
11. Qb5+
{ This is a precise move that forces Black to play c6, which completely blocks the bishop on c8  (note that Bd7 drops the pawn on b7)  . }
11... c6 12. Qc5
{ The queen is very active on c5 and actively prevents Black from achieving the desired e5 or c5 pawn breaks. }
12... Bd7
{ If Black tries to exchange the queens with  12...Qe7  , White can just ignore it with  13.O-O-O  as  13...Qxc5  14.dxc5  ± is an even better version for White. We now have control over the d-file and can plant the knight on the strong d6 outpost with Nd2-e4-d6. }
13. O-O-O
{ White has a clear and stable, long-lasting advantage. Black's bishop is out of the game and it will be very hard for Black to achieve either the c5 or e5 breaks. White's knight on the other hand is enjoying life and will be excellently placed on the e5 outpost. White can also consider pushing the h-pawn down the board to create some weaknesses on the kingside and even activate the h1 rook with the ROVER  (rook up and over!)  maneuver Rh1-h3-f3. }
