[White "2. 3...Nc6"]
[Black "3...Nc6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nb4 5. Nc3 Nf6
{ White should forge ahead with } 6. e5
{ gaining space and pushing the knight back. } 6... Nd7
{ The intermediate  6...Nxd3  is an even better version of the main line  7.Qxd3  Nd7  8.Bg5  as White saved a tempo on the move a3. }
7. Bg5 Be7 8. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ The exchange of dark-squared bishops greatly favors White. Notice that white's pawns on d4 and e5 are on dark squares, and hence the dark-squared bishop was White's bad bishop &#40and Black's good one&#41. }
9. a3 { This is White's easiest route to a slight advantage. } 9... Nxd3+ 10.
Qxd3 O-O
{ The immediate pawn break  10...c5  runs into  11.dxc5  Qxc5   If  11...Nxc5  12.Qe3  O-O  13.Nd4±  followed by O-O gives White a clear edge.  12.Nb5  and now  12...O-O  is strongly met by  13.Ng5  g6  14.f4  Qb6  15.Qh3  h5  16.Nd6+−  with an overwhelming position.    Preparing the c5 break with   10...a6  to stop any Nb5-d6 jumps can be met by  11.h4  gaining space on the kingside  11...c5  12.h5  h6  13.Qe3  O-O  14.Ne2  Preparing to recapture on d4 with the knight.  14...cxd4  15.Nexd4  b5  16.O-O-O  White's king will actually be perfectly safe on the queenside. It's Black's king on g8 that will come under fire after  16...Nb6  17.Nd2  Bd7  18.g4  with the idea f4 and g4-g5, blasting open Black's kingside. }
11. h4
{ White has the initiative and can continue with Ng5, O-O-O and even h4-h5-h6, with a strong attack on Black's king. Note that the bishop on c8 is still stuck behind his own pawn chain. }
