[Black "3...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nf6
{ 3...Nf6 is one of Black's main responses against both the Tarrasch with 3. Nd2 and the Classical with 3. Nc3 variations of the French Defense. A lot of Black players play this move thinking it will transpose to the Tarrasch.   However, 3...Nf6 is not such a great move against the 3. Bd3 variation. The main difference compared to the 3. Nd2 Tarrasch is that the knight on b1 has not been committed to d2. This might seem very subtle but it ensures White will get an advantage in every line. }
4. e5 { Going forward with } 4... Ne4
{ is a mistake. The knight is very short on squares here and can easily be trapped. }
5. Nh3 c5
{ 5...Be7  such that the knight can retreat to g5 runs into the double-attack  6.Qg4±  threatening both Qxg7 and Bxe4, which Black is unable to meet. }
6. f3 { traps Black's knight. } 6... Qh4+ { is just one check. } 7. Kf1
{ White will pick up Black's knight on the next turn with a decisive advantage. }
