[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. 3...Nf6"]
[Black "3...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nf6
{ 3... Nf6 is one of Black's main responses against both the Tarrasch with 3.Nd2 and the Classical with 3.Nc3 variations of the French Defense. A lot of Black players play this move thinking it will transpose to the Tarrasch. However, 3... Nf6 is not such a great move against the 3. Bd3 variation. The main difference compared to the 3. Nd2 Tarrasch is that the knight on b1 has not been committed to d2. This might seem very subtle but it ensures White will get an advantage in every line. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. Ne2
{ The knight is much better placed on e2 than on f3 in this structure. This is because it supports the d4 pawn without blocking the f4-f5 pawn break. Furthermore, apart from this break, oftentimes stronger is to transfer the e2 knight to h5  (via g3 or f4)  , hitting the pawn on g7 which is surprisingly difficult to defend, and follow up with Qg4/h5 with a strong attack.   Alternatives such as 5. f4 and 5. Nf3 have also been tried in practice but are clearly inferior to the text. }
5... c5 6. c3
{ As the knight is still on b1, we are able to strengthen the center with c3. }
6... Nc6
{ Trying to exchange the light-squared bishops with  6...b6  loses too much time.  7.O-O  Ba6  8.f4  Bxd3  9.Qxd3  g6  Black prevents f5 but White can strike in the center with  10.c4±  White takes advantage of his lead in development to blast open the center with a clear edge. }
7. a3
{ is the engines' top choice and it effectively puts the 3...Nf6 variation out of business.   7.O-O  is premature because after  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  Nb4  Black will gain a bunch of tempos against the bishop on d3  9.Bb5  a6  10.Ba4  b5  11.Bb3  a5  Black gained a lot of space on the queenside and the bishop is misplaced on b3.  In the French, White's bishop should be placed on the b1-h7 diagonal, where it supports the f4-f5 pawn break and eyes the pawn on h7  (which can be targeted later on with Ng3 and Qh5)  .   This is the reason why White should play 7. a3! instead, stopping any ...Nb4 ideas and maintaining the bishop on d3. }
7... a5
{ Stops b4 but permanently weakens the b5 square, which White can later use. This square can be fixed with a4 in the future when it'll make a strong outpost for White's pieces. }
8. O-O Be7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Nf4 { Qh5 is coming next with a strong attack. } *

