[Black "3...Nf6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nf6
{ 3... Nf6 is one of Black's main responses against both the Tarrasch with 3.Nd2 and the Classical with 3.Nc3 variations of the French Defense. A lot of Black playersplay this move thinking it will transpose to the Tarrasch. However, 3... Nf6 is not such a great move against the 3. Bd3 variation. The main difference compared to the 3. Nd2 Tarrasch is that the knight on b1 has not been committed to d2. This might seem very subtle but it ensures White will get an advantage in every line. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. Ne2
{ The knight is much better placed on e2 than on f3 in this structure. This is because it supports the d4 pawn without blocking the f4-f5 pawn break. Furthermore, apart from this break, oftentimes stronger is to transfer the e2 knight to h5  (via g3 or f4)  , hitting the pawn on g7 which is surprisingly difficult to defend, and follow up with Qg4/h5 with a strong attack.   Alternatives such as 5. f4 and 5. Nf3 have also been tried in practice but are clearly inferior to the text. }
5... c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. a3
{ 7.O-O  is premature because after  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  Nb4  Black will gain a bunch of tempos against the Bd3.  9.Bb5  a6  10.Ba4  b5  11.Bb3  a5  Black gained a lot of space on the queenside and the bishop is misplaced on b3.   In the French, White's bishop should be placed on the b1-h7 diagonal, where it supports the f4-f5 pawn break and eyes the pawn on h7  (which can be targeted later on with Qh5 and Ng3)  .   This is the reason why White should play 7.a3! instead, stopping any Nb4 ideas and preserving the bishop on d3. }
7... Qb6 8. b4 { 8. Bc2 is also possible but the text is stronger. } 8... c4
{ Trying to close down the queenside does not work due to a very concrete reason. }
9. Bc2 a5
{ Trying to create something on the queenside is Black's best try.   Natural developing moves like   9...Be7  allow White to gain even more space on the queenside with  10.a4  O-O  11.O-O  a5  12.b5  Na7  13.Nf4  +− The center and the queenside are completely stable. Now White has a free hand to start an attack on the kingside  (with Qg4, Nh5, Re1-e3-g3 etc)  . Since Black has less space on this side of the board, Black's king doesn't stand a chance. }
10. b5 { This pawn sacrifice is very strong and basically refutes 8... c4. }
10... Qxb5
{ 8...Na7  is out of question as after  9.a4  +-  White has a free hand on the kingside and Black has zero counterplay. }
11. a4 Qa6 12. Na3
{ For just one pawn, we completely eliminated Black's counterplay on the queenside. White will continue with O-O, Na3-b5, and Ba3  (exchanging the dark-squared bishops greatly favors White)  , followed by Nf4-h5 and Qg4. The rook lift Re1-e3-g3 is also a typical maneuver to keep in mind. White has a strategically winning position.  Based on beta tester feedback and because Chessable has a wide audience, I've decided to mark the next 4 illustrative lines as alternative variations so that casual/club players are not overwhelmed by having to train 20+ moves of theory.  NOTE: I still highly recommend checking out these variations to see the typical plans and ideas  .   Ambitious and/or higher-rated players can choose to train these alternative variations if they see fit. }
*

