12. Na3
{ For just one pawn, we completely eliminated Black's counterplay on the queenside. White will continue with O-O, Na3-b5 and Ba3  (exchanging the dark-squared bishops greatly favors White)  , followed by Nf4-h5 and Qg4. The rook lift Re1-e3-g3 is also a typical manuever to keep in mind. White has a strategically winning position. }
12... Na7
{ Black stops Nb5 but he has no answer to White's initiative on the kingside. }
13. O-O Be7 14. Nf4 O-O 15. Qh5 { Threatening Qxh7 checkmate. } 15... g6 16.
Nxg6
{ This tactical shot leads to a forced mate in 17  (!)  .   16...fxg6  17.Bxg6  hxg6  18.Qxg6  Kh8  19.Re1  Black is defenseless against the checkmating threat of Re1-e3-h3. }
