{ The knight is much better placed on e2 than on f3 in this structure. This is because it supports the d4 pawn without blocking the f4-f5 pawn break. Furthermore, apart from this break, oftentimes stronger is to transfer the e2 knight to h5  (via g3 or f4)  , hitting the pawn on g7 which is surprisingly difficult to defend, and follow up with Qg4/h5 with a strong attack.   Alternatives such as 5. f4 and 5. Nf3 have also been tried in practice but are clearly inferior to the text. }
5... c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. a3
{ 7.O-O  is premature because after  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  Nb4  Black will gain a bunch of tempos against the Bd3.  9.Bb5  a6  10.Ba4  b5  11.Bb3  a5  Black gained a lot of space on the queenside and the bishop on b3 is misplaced.   In the French, White's bishop should be placed on the b1-h7 diagonal, where it supports the f4-f5 pawn break and eyes the pawn on h7  (which can be targeted later on with Qh5 and Ng3)  .   This is the reason why White should play 7.a3! instead, stopping any Nb4 ideas and preserving the bishop on d3. }
7... Qb6 8. b4 { 8. Bc2 is also possible but the text is stronger. } 8... c4
{ Trying to close down the queenside does not work due to a very concrete reason. }
9. Bc2 a5 10. b5
{ This pawn sacrifice is very strong and basically refutes 8... c4. } 10...
Qxb5
{ 8...Na7  is out of question as after  9.a4  +-  White has a free hand on the kingside and Black has zero counterplay. }
11. a4 Qa6
{ 11... Qb6  is inferior as Black will have to place the queen on a6 anyways after Na3 and Rb1. }
12. Na3
{ For just one-pawn, we completely eliminated Black's counterplay on the queenside. White will continue with O-O, Na3-b5 and Ba3  (exchanging the dark-squared bishops)  , followed by Nf4-h5, Qg4 and f4-f5. White has a strategically winning position. }
12... Be7 13. Nb5 Qb6 14. Rb1 { Nd6+ picking up the queen is White's threat. }
14... O-O 15. Nf4 Na7 16. Qh5
{ Black has no defense against White's strong attack. There are 3 pieces already in the attack and the rook on h1 will soon join after h4 and Rh3-g3 or O-O followed by Re1-e3-h3. }
16... g6 17. Qh6
{ White is threatening Nh5 and Qg7 checkmate. Note that Black will not be able to capture the knight on h5 due to Qxh7 checkmate. 17. Nxg6 was also winning. }
17... f5 18. Nxg6 hxg6 19. Qxg6+ Kh8 20. h4
{ The ROVER  (rook up and over)  is inbound once again and Black's king will be mated shortly thereafter. }
