1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nf6
{ 3... Nf6 is one of Black's main responses against both the Tarrasch with 3.Nd2 and the Classical with 3.Nc3 variations of the French Defense. A lot of Black players play this move thinking it will transpose to the Tarrasch. However, 3... Nf6 is not such a great move against the 3. Bd3 variation. The main difference compared to the 3. Nd2 Tarrasch is that the knight on b1 has not been committed to d2. This might seem very subtle but it ensures White will get an advantage in every line. }
4. e5 Nfd7 5. Ne2
{ The knight is much better placed on e2 than on f3 in this structure. This is because it supports the d4 pawn without blocking the f4-f5 pawn break. Furthermore, apart from this break, oftentimes stronger is to transfer the e2 knight to h5  (via g3 or f4)  , hitting the pawn on g7 which is surprisingly difficult to defend, and follow up with Qg4/h5 with a strong attack.   Alternatives such as 5. f4 and 5. Nf3 have also been tried in practice but are clearly inferior to the text. }
5... c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. a3
{ 7.O-O  is premature because after  7...cxd4  8.cxd4  Nb4  Black will gain a bunch of tempos against the Bd3.  9.Bb5  a6  10.Ba4  b5  11.Bb3  a5  Black gained a lot of space on the queenside and the bishop on b3 is misplaced.   In the French, White's bishop should be placed on the b1-h7 diagonal, where it supports the f4-f5 pawn break and eyes the pawn on h7  (which can be targeted later on with Qh5 and Ng3)  .   This is the reason why White should play 7.a3! instead, stopping any Nb4 ideas and preserving the bishop on d3. }
7... Qb6 8. b4 { 8. Bc2 is also possible but the text is stronger. } 8... cxd4
9. cxd4 a5
{ 9...f6  is also no good on account of  10.Be3  fxe5  11.dxe5  Qd8  12.f4  Be7  13.Nd4  +− Black cannot meet both of White's threats of Nxe6 and Qh5+. }
10. Qa4
{ 10.b5  is a blunder as we lose control over the c5 square. Black can now win a pawn with  10...Nxd4  as after  11.Be3  Black has  11...Bc5  −+   10.Qa4 pins the a5 pawn  (...axb4 would drop the rook on a8)  and now White is now threatening b5 as the queen from a4 would cover the d4 pawn. }
10... Be7 11. b5 Ncxe5 { Black sacrifices a knight for two pawns. } 12. dxe5
Nxe5 13. Bc2
{ White moves the bishop to safety and will finish his development with Nbc3 and 0-0. }
13... Bd7 14. Nbc3 O-O 15. O-O
{ Next on the agenda is Be3, bringing White's last minor piece into the game with a tempo on the queen on b6. White is clearly better and his extra piece will eventually decide the game. Black does not have enough compensation. I'd encourage you to spend some time playing around with the engine in this position in case you are not convinced. }
