1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Ne2 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. a3
{ The other typical French pawn break } 7... f6 { White can jump with } 8. Nf4
{ immediately putting pressure on the e6 pawn. } 8... Qe7 9. exf6 Qxf6
{ Alternatively  9...Nxf6  can be met with  10.O-O  cxd4  11.cxd4  g6  12.Be3  Bg7  13.Nd2⩲  followed by Re1 and Rc1 with a pleasant advantage. Black's pawn structure is compromised and he still hasn't solved the problem with his light-squared bishop. }
10. O-O
{ With the idea Re1 to attack the e6 pawn. Now follows a relatively long semi-forced variation where with best play by both sides, White will emerge up a pawn. }
10... cxd4
{ 10...Nb6  is met by the surprisingly strong retreating move  11.Nh3  making way for Bg5  11...cxd4  12.cxd4  Bd6  13.Bg5  Qf7  14.Be3  Defending the pawn on e3 and vacating the g5 square for Ng5  14...h6  ?!  15.f4  ⩲ White is slightly better due to his strong control over the center. He can continue with Nd2-f3-e5, occupying the strong e5 outpost  (note that Black on the other hand cannot plant a knight on e4)  . }
11. Nxe6 { Strong and visually appealing! } 11... Qxe6 12. Re1
{ Attacking the queen, which is pinned to the king on e8. Thus, Black has to play }
12... Nde5 13. Bf4 dxc3 14. Bxe5 Nxe5 15. Qh5+
{ Forking the knight and the king. } 15... g6 16. Qxe5 Qxe5
{ Black should go for  16...Bg7  and after  17.Bb5  Kd8  18.Qxe6  Bxe6  19.Nxc3  Bxc3  20.bxc3  Bf7  21.c4=  White has a small initiative, which Black should be able to neutralize with precise play. }
17. Rxe5+ Kf7 18. Nxc3 { The natural } 18... d4
{ is actually a big mistake.   18...Bg7  is Black's best try but after  19.Rxd5  Be6  20.Rb5⩲  White has an extra pawn and wants to play Ne4 next, threatening a fork with Nd6. Black does have some compensation in the form of the bishop pair but, in the end, a pawn is a pawn. Only White can win this position. }
19. Ne4
{ White's rook, knight and bishop are already developed and swarming around Black's king. Conversely, Black's pieces are all on the back rank. White thus has a clear advantage and wants to play Rc1 next, threatening to invade the 7th rank decisively with Rc7+. }
