[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 3..c5"]
[Black "4...Qxd5?! #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 c5
{ Black immediately strikes in the center, trying to challenge White's e4 and d4 pawn duo. This might transpose to a variation of the exchange French, where Black will be left with an isolated pawn on d5, which is not everyone's cup of tea. }
4. exd5 Qxd5
{ This natural recapture is actually a mistake. At first sight, it seems that Black will win a pawn as the queen is attacking the d4 and g2 pawns simultaneously. }
5. Nc3
{ White simply ignores both Black's threats and develops with tempo. It turns out that Black cannot capture either pawn. }
5... Qxg2 6. Be4
{ The queen is trapped and Black will have to sacrifice it for the rook on h1. White is already winning. }
