5... Qxd4 { This capture also does not work. } 6. Nb5
{ Hitting the queen on d4 and threatening Nc7+, forking the king on e8 and the a8 rook. }
6... Qe5+ 7. Ne2
{ Blocking the check and preparing Bf4, renewing the threat of Nc7+ } 7... Na6
{ This is the only way of preventing Nc7+. } 8. Bf4 Qxb2
{ This does not work. } 9. Rb1 Qf6
{ 9...Qxa2  10.Nbc3  Qa5  11.Bb5  Black cannot block the check and is faced with a grim choice: give up the queen with ...Qxb5 or play  11...Ke7  when White has a forced mate in 8 starting with  12.Qd6  Kf6  13.Be5  Kf5  14.Bd3  Kg4  15.f3  Kh5  16.g4  Kg5  17.h4  Kh6  18.Bf4  g5  19.Qxf8 }
10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Bb5+
{ Hitting the king on e8 and the bishop on d6. What follows is a forced variation after which White will emerge with a winning position. }
11... Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Kxd7 13. Qxd6+ Kc8
{ 13...Ke8  loses to  14.Rxb7  Nb8  15.O-O+−  Rd1 is coming next. Black is busted. }
14. Qf8+ Qd8
{ Practically forced.   The alternative  14...Kd7  leads to a forced checkmate in 10 moves  15.Rd1  Kc6  16.Qd6  Kb5  17.Qd7  Ka5  18.a4  With the unstoppable mating threat of Qb5. }
15. Qxg7 Ne7 16. Qxf7
{ Material is equal but Black's position is in disarray. The e6 pawn is currently under attack and the king on c8 is extremely weak. White will follow up with O-O and Rd1 with a decisive advantage. }
