1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 c5
{ Black immediately strikes in the center, trying to challenge White's e4 and d4 pawn duo. This might transpose to a variation of the exchange French, where Black will be left with an isolated pawn on d5, which is not everyone's cup of tea. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Nf3
{ The idea is to take on c5 only when the black bishop is developed, and then control the isolated pawn by occupying the d4-square, mainly with a knight. Also, if Black plays c4 then we'll play b3, after moving away our light-squared bishop, of course, and we'll get the centre, some more space and easier play.   Black can also release the tension and try to gain some space on the queenside with c4. However, White will easily break this up with b3. }
5... c4 6. Be2
{ As we said, we'll play b3 next move and get a free centre, some more space and easier play. }
6... Nf6 7. b3 cxb3 { This is practically forced. } 8. axb3
{ White recaptures with the a-pawn, opening up the a-file for his rook and retains the possibility of breaking with c4 later on. }
8... Nc6 9. O-O Be7 10. c4 O-O 11. Na3
{ This is an interesting setup. White will put the knight on c2 and push c5, followed by b4-b5 gaining a lot of space on the queenside and pushing back Black's pieces. In particular, once the Nc6 is kicked back, the e5 square becomes an ideal outpost for the Nf3. }
