[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 c5
{ Black immediately strikes in the center, trying to challenge White's e4 and d4 pawn duo. This might transpose to a variation of the exchange French, where Black will be left with an isolated pawn on d5, which is not everyone's cup of tea. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O Nf6 7. Re1+ Be7
{ This is the right way of dealing with the check. } 8. dxc5
{ We waited for Black to play Be7 before capturing on c5, which will make Black waste another tempo with Bxc5 to regain the pawn. }
8... O-O 9. Bg5 { Developing the bishop to its most active square. } 9... Bxc5
10. Nc3
{ The knight is better placed on c3 than on d2. From c3, it not only controls the e4 square but also puts pressure on the pawn on d5. Furthermore, it leaves the d-file unblocked, where White will place his heavy pieces to attack the d5 pawn. }
10... Be6 11. a3
{ Not only stopping ...Nb4 but supporting a future b2-b4-b5 advance. This would grant White control over the e5 square, which can be taken advantage of with Nf3-e5 later on. }
11... h6 12. Bh4 Re8 13. Qd2
{ White is on the more comfortable side of equality. Black has an isolated pawn on d5 and not much activity to show for it. White should continue with Rad1 and then consider pushing the b-pawn with b4-b5, kicking back the bishop and taking control over the e5 square. Another idea is to place a piece on the e5 square, for example with Bg3 followed by Ne5.  Here is a sample line:   12...Be7  13.Rad1  a6  14.h3  Qb6  We have been following the game Deac,B  (2575)  -Marin,M  (2543)  Olanesti 2018 where White played 15. Qc1. Instead  15.b4  with the idea Na4 would have given White a slight advantage. }
