1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 c5
{ Black immediately strikes in the center, trying to challenge White's e4 and d4 pawn duo. This might transpose to a variation of the exchange French, where Black will be left with an isolated pawn on d5, which is not everyone's cup of tea. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O cxd4
{ This capture is premature as it releases the pressure on the d4 pawn. } 7.
Re1+ { Developing with tempo } 7... Be7 8. h3
{ This is arguably White's best move in the position. It stops any ideas of Bg4 and restricts Black's light-squared bishop. All the desirable active squares for this bishop, f5 and g4, are now firmly under White's control.   8.Bg5  might seem attractive but it is well met by  8...h6!  9.Bxe7  Ngxe7  10.h3  Qb6  Hitting b2 and forcing White's queen to the passive c1 square  11.Qc1  O-O =  Black comfortably equalized and went on to win in 0-1 Liang,A @@StartBracket@@2572@@EndBracket@@-Durarbayli,V @@StartBracket@@2629@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2018. }
8... Nf6 9. Nbd2 { Heading to b3 with the idea Nb3xd4. } 9... O-O 10. Nb3 Re8
11. Nbxd4
{ White has regained the pawn and managed to blockade the isolani. White's knight on d4 is very active. }
11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd7 13. c3
{ This is quite a favorable version of the IQP for White. Black's pieces are all in the last 3 ranks and he has very little activity to show for the isolated d5 pawn. White's knight on d4 is very powerful and can hardly be challenged. White should continue with Be3 and then develop the queen to f3 or b3, depending on what Black does. Another typical idea is to double on the e-file with Re2 and Rae1. }
