1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 c5
{ Black immediately strikes in the center, trying to challenge White's e4 and d4 pawn duo. This might transpose to a variation of the exchange French, where Black will be left with an isolated pawn on d5, which is not everyone's cup of tea. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Nf3
{ The idea is to take on c5 only when the black bishop is developed, and then control the isolated pawn by occupying the d4-square, mainly with a knight. Also, if Black plays c4 then we'll play b3, after moving away our light-squared bishop, of course, and we'll get the centre, some more space and easier play. }
5... Nf6
{ This move was recommended by GM Mihail Marin in a French Defense repertoire database. }
6. c3 Nc6
{ Marin stopped here and said that Black will be fine with cxd4 after White castles. However, White can still ask some questions with: }
7. O-O cxd4
{ Black should capture on d4. If he develops the bishop to e7 or d6, White will capture on c5  (making Black spend another tempo recapturing the pawn with Bxc5)  and Black will be left with an isolated pawn on d5. }
8. Re1+ Be7 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. cxd4 O-O 11. Nc3 Be6 12. Bc2
{ Even though Black is objectively fine, I believe White is slightly more comfortable. Next on the agenda is Qd3 and Bg5, threatening checkmate on h7. After Black parries this threat, White can put the Qf3 and target the d5 pawn with Bb3 with some annoying pressure. }
