{ Black immediately strikes in the center, trying to challenge White's e4 and d4 pawn duo. This might transpose to a variation of the exchange French, where Black will be left with an isolated pawn on d5, which is not everyone's cup of tea. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Nf3
{ The idea is to take on c5 only when the black bishop is developed, and then control the isolated pawn by occupying the d4-square, mainly with a knight. Also, if Black plays c4 then we'll play b3, after moving away our light-squared bishop, of course, and we'll get the centre, some more space and easier play. }
5... Nf6 6. c3 c4 { Immediately locking down the center. } 7. Bc2 Bd6
{ 7...Be7  fails to control the e5 square. After  8.O-O  O-O  White can hop into e5 with  9.Ne5⩲  followed by Re1 and Nd2-f3 with a slight advantage. }
8. Qe2+ { Stopping Black from castling short. } 8... Qe7 9. Qxe7+ Kxe7
{ 9...Bxe7  is also possible. After  10.O-O  O-O  11.Re1  Re8  12.Nbd2=  White can continue with Nf1, Bg5, and Ne3 to pressure the d5 pawn. }
10. O-O Re8
{ This was all recommended in the Chessable course 'Lifetime Repertoires: the French Defense' by GM Anish Giri, who concluded that Black was equal.  I agree with his assessment, but nevertheless think that White has easier play. }
11. Re1+ Kf8 12. Rxe8+ Kxe8 13. Bg5
{ Developing the bishop to its most active post. } 13... Nbd7
{ And here Leela likes } 14. Nh4
{ intending to hop into f5. Another idea pointed out by the neural network engines is to play g3 followed by Ng2 and then exchange the dark-squared bishops with Bf4. }
14... g6 { Stopping ...Nf5. } 15. g3
{ White can continue with Ng2 followed by Bf4 to exchange the dark-squared bishops. Note that all of our pawns are on dark squares, so this exchange greatly favors us.  Black has slightly overextended on the queenside and his d5 pawn is a target. White can attack it with Ng2-f4 and Nd2-f1-e3.   Finally, Black's queenside pawn structure can also be undermined with a2-a4 and b2-b3.  All in all, White has easier play and retains some slight pressure. }
