[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. 3...dxe4 Part I"]
[Black "5...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4
{ We now tackle the main line where Black captures on e4. I am not claiming White gets an advantage in every line in this variation if Black plays very precisely.   However, what I can guarantee is that you will at the very least get a more comfortable position with clear plans where you will know exactly what to do. Even in the long forcing lines where Black is objectively fine, we are going to pose as many practical problems as possible.   After analyzing these variations thoroughly, I found that 3. Bd3 is much more challenging than I initially thought. Black needs to be aware of several subtleties to be able to equalize and one misstep can easily land him in a much worse position. }
4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 Nc6
{ is quite rare and was most notably played by 2600+ GM Mateusz Bartel in 2016. It didn't pick up much of a following, probably due to the lines I'm about to show. Black's idea behind 5...Nc6 is to break in the center with ...e5 as soon as possible. }
6. Ne2 e5
{ 6...Bd6  has also been tried but allows White to play  7.Na3  intending to go after Black's bishop with  Nc4  . This position only occurred once and Black immediately went wrong with  7...Bxa3   Better is  7....O-O  but after  8.Nc4  Re8  9.O-O  Black will find it hard to break with ...e5 under good conditions.  8.bxa3  O-O  9.O-O  Rb8  10.Bg5⩲  gave White a significant advantage in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Volovich, V @@StartBracket@@2147@@EndBracket@@-Mischuk, D @@StartBracket@@2358@@EndBracket@@ Voronezh 2020. The bishop pair advantage and the open b-file far outweighs the double a-pawns. }
7. Bxc6+
{ I'm usually not a big fan of giving up the bishop pair, but here the damage to Black's pawn structure is severe and more than justifies it. }
7... bxc6 8. O-O Bd6
{ This is Black's most popular move, simply defending the e5 pawn.   Worse is  8...e4  which was played only a handful of times. The e4 pawn is more of a vulnerability than an asset.  9.c4  Be7  10.Nbc3  O-O  11.Ng3  immediately targets the e4 pawn.  11...Bg4  12.Qd2  Qd7  13.h3!  improves over the game Jahn, C @@StartBracket@@2198@@EndBracket@@-Likavsky, T @@StartBracket@@2485@@EndBracket@@ Triesen 2007.  13...Be6  14.b3⩲  Black will be hard pressed to keep the  e4  pawn alive. }
9. dxe5 Bxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Rd1+ Bd7 12. Nbc3
{ The pin along the d-file is quite annoying for Black and his queenside pawn structure is severely compromised. }
12... Rb8 13. b3
{ Moving the pawn out of danger so as to develop the dark-squared bishop next. }
13... Kc8 14. Bf4
{ White was clearly better and brought the point home in 1-0  (36)  Blauhut, H  (2114)  -Walseth, T  (1963)  Kragero 2020. }
