6... Bd6 { White should immediately attack the bishop with } 7. Nb5 Bb4+ 8. c3
a6
{ was recommended by GM Dmitry Kryakvin in the book 'The Modern French Defence', which is a novelty according to my database. }
9. Nxc7+
{ The critical test.   The alternative  9.cxb4  axb5  10.Ne2  Nd5=  is harmless. }
9... Qxc7 10. cxb4 e5 { A strong move, with the idea ...e4 to hit our bishop. }
11. Nh3
{ This is the best square for the knight. Black will play ...e4 next, so we reserve the e2 square for the bishop. Our knight can then join the action with Nh3-f4. }
11... e4 12. Be2 { The natural } 12... O-O { is already an inaccuracy. } 13.
Nf4 Nb6 14. Qb3
{ takes control over the d5 square, stopping ...Nd5 for the time being and gives us the option of swinging the queen over to the kingside. }
14... Rd8
{ Possible better is  14...Bg4  although after  15.Bxg4  Nxg4  16.O-O⩲  White is a pawn up. h3 followed by Be3 should be enough for an advantage. }
15. Qg3
{ We're not afraid of giving up the d4 pawn to speed up our development. }
15... Rxd4 16. Be3 Rd7
{ 16...Rxb4?!  is too greedy. After  17.Rc1  Qe5  18.b3  Bf5  19.O-O±  Black is in big trouble as his rook is almost trapped on b4. }
17. Rc1 { Developing another piece with tempo. } 17... Qd6 18. O-O
{ with the idea Bc5. The pawn advance b4-b5 is also in the cards. White's bishop pair is a force to be reckoned with and Black's pieces are uncoordinated. }
