{ The polish super grandmaster Jan-Krzysztof Duda played the rare 5...Nbd7 against 2600+ GM Sergey Fedorchuk in the 2017 European Blitz Championship. }
6. Nc3
{ This is stronger than the more common 6. Ne2. The point is that 6. Ne2 allows Black to equalize after ...Bd6 and ...e5 &#40with 6.Nc3 we have the option of disrupting this plan with Nb5&#41. }
6... a6
{ Preparing the b5 advance with ...a6 first is also possible. Black wants to play Bd6 and, with this move, he prevents White from playing Nb5. }
7. Nge2
{ We simply continue our development. Note that due to the Bf3 Black must first play ...Rb8 before he can push ...b5. }
7... Bd6 8. Ng3
{ is the simplest option.   8.O-O  is also possible and transposes to the text after  8...O-O  9.Ng3  .   For the more adventurous and aggressive players  8.g4  is also very interesting. The main line I analyzed goes  8...O-O  9.h4  Rb8  9.g5  Very aggressive indeed!  9...Nd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Bxd5  White is a pawn up but is underdeveloped. Black needs to be precise to not just end up down a pawn for no compensation  12...Re8  is one of Black's best tries  13.Qd3  Nb6  14.Bb3  Bg4  15.Be3  Blocking the e-file and making way for O-O-O  Nd5  16.O-O-O  Bf3  17.Rhg1=  This position is objectively equal but Black needs to be precise to maintain the balance. After all, White is still a pawn up. }
8... O-O
{ 8...e5  allows  9.Nf5  O-O  10.Nxd6  gaining the bishop pair and spoiling Black's structure  10...cxd6  11.O-O⩲ }
9. O-O Rb8 { Black is now ready to push ...b5, so White should play } 10. a4
{ Ensuring that our rook on a1 will control the a-file after we chop on b5. }
10... b5 11. axb5 axb5 { As mentioned, we got the a-file for free. } 12. Qd3
{ Developing the queen and hitting the pawn on b5. } 12... b4 13. Nce4 Bb7
{ 13...Nxe4  14.Nxe4  Bb7  15.Ra7  Transposes to the text. } 14. Ra7
{ Placing a rook on the 7th rank is always great! } 14... Bxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4
16. Qxe4 Nf6 17. Qc6
{ White is slightly better due to the bishop pair @@StartBracket@@the light-squared bishop is extremely well placed, preventing Black from playing ...Ra8@@EndBracket@@ and the very active Qc6 and Ra7. White can also look to target the b4-pawn with Qc4 and Bd2. Doubling on the a-file with Rfa1 later on is also possible. That being said, Black has no apparent weaknesses and is quite solid. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. 3...dxe4 Part I"]
[Black "5...Nbd7 6. Nc3 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
{ This position is reminiscent of the Rubinstein variation of the French Defense. In the Rubinstein, Black usually develops his light squared bishop along the b7/c6-h1 diagonal, either by b6+Bb7 or Bd7-c6. By placing our bishop on f3, we prevent said developing scheme. Of course, the knight now cannot occupy the f3 square but it will be well placed on e2. }
5... Nbd7
{ The polish super grandmaster Jan-Krzysztof Duda played the rare 5... Nbd7 against 2600+ GM Sergey Fedorchuk in the 2017 European Blitz Championship in Katowice. }
6. Nc3 c6
{ This is another way of preventing Nb5, with the idea to play ...Bd6 and break in the center with ...e5. It may look quite passive at first sight but it allows Black to eventually equalize. }
7. Nge2 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Ng3 { Clearing the e-file for Re1. } 9... Qc7
{ Black is getting ready to break with ...e5 } 10. Re1 Re8
{ The immediate   10...e5  leads to similar play as the mainline  11.Be3  Re8  12.h3  exd4  13.Bxd4  Rxe1+  14.Qxe1  Be5  15.Qd2  Bxd4  16.Qxd4  Ne5  17.Be4=  After exchanging a pair of rooks and minor pieces, the position is objectively equal. Nevertheless, White is slightly more comfortable due to his more active pieces. }
11. b3
{ The bishop on c1 does not have a good square on the c1-h6 diagonal, so fianchettoing it on b2 is natural. }
11... e5 12. Bb2 exd4 13. Rxe8+ Nxe8 14. Qxd4 Ne5 15. Be4
{ Black has managed to successfully achieve the e5 break and has therefore objectively equalized. That being said, White is on the better side of equality here thanks to his more active pieces. White can continue with moves like Rd1, Bf5 and Ne4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. 3...dxe4 Part I"]
[Black "5...Nbd7 [6. Ne2 Alternative]"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4
{ We now tackle the main line where Black captures on e4. I am not claiming White gets an advantage in every line in this variation if Black plays very precisely. However, what I can guarantee is that you will at the very least get a more comfortable position with clear plans where you will know exactly what to do. Even in the long forcing lines where Black is objectively fine, we are going to pose as many practical problems as possible. After analyzing these variations thoroughly, I found that 3. Bd3 is much more challenging than I initially thought. Black needs to be aware of several subtleties to be able to equalize and one misstep can easily land him in a much worse position. }
4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
{ This position is reminiscent of the Rubinstein variation of the French Defense. In the Rubinstein, Black usually develops his light squared bishop along the b7/c6-h1 diagonal, either by b6+Bb7 or Bd7-c6. By placing our bishop on f3, we prevent said developing scheme. Of course, the knight now cannot occupy the f3 square but it will be well placed on e2. }
5... Nbd7
{ I first came across this rare move when the polish super grandmaster Jan-Krzysztof Duda played it against 2600+ GM Sergey Fedorchuk in the 2017 European Blitz Championship in Katowice. It has also been tried by other strong grandmasters such as GM Eduardas Rozentalis and GM Andrey Sumets.   The main idea of 5... Nbd7 is to break in the center with 6... e5, which would open the c8-h3 diagonal for the bishop on c8. }
6. Ne2
{ This is an alternative recommendation to 6. Nc3, leading to a position where White is ever so slightly better. It has the advantage of cutting down on the number of lines you need to learn but is arguably less ambitious. I'll let you decide which option you prefer. }
6... e5
{ Preparing the e5 break   with  6...Bd6  transposes to the5...Bd6 #3 variation. }
7. O-O e4 8. Ng3
{ Don't worry, we're not blundering a piece as Re1 is coming next! } 8... exf3
9. Re1+ Be7 10. Nf5 { allows us to recoup the sacrificed piece. } 10... Nb6 11.
Rxe7+ Kf8 12. Re5 fxg2 13. Nc3
{ gives White a clear advantage.   Black's king is in no man's land and White is even threatening  13...--  14.Nxg7!  with the point that  14...Kxg7  loses to  15.Bh6+!  Kxh6  16.Qc1+  Kg7  17.Qg5+  Kf8  18.Qh6+  Kg8  19.Rg5# }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. 3...dxe4 Part I"]
[Black "5...Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 Bd6
{ This interesting move was played by the French Defense expert 2600+ GM Andrei Istratescu in a blitz game in 2019. Black's plan is quite ambitious: he wants to take advantage of the fact that knight is not on f3 and break in the center with e5 after ...O-O. If Black achieves the e5 break under good conditions, he'll solve the problem of the c8 bishop and immediately equalize. }
6. Ne2
{ 6. Nc3 was played by GM Bogdan-Daniel Deac in the aforementioned blitz game. However, I believe the b1 knight should not be placed on c3. White should take advantage of the fact that Black has played placed the bishop on d6  (as opposed to the more conventional ...Be7)  and route the b1 knight to c4 via d2. }
6... O-O 7. Nd2
{ The knight is coming to c4, where it will hit the bishop on d6 and clamp down on the e5 square, effectively preventing any e5 breaks. }
7... e5
{ If Black wants to break on e5, he has to do it now. Otherwise, White would have played Nc4 and this pawn break would no longer be available. }
8. dxe5 Bxe5 9. O-O Nc6
{ 9...c6  blunts the bishop on f3 but also takes away the c6 square from the Nb8 and severely weakens the d6 square. White can immediately take advantage of the latter with  10.Nc4  Bc7  and  11.b3  Be6  12.Ba3  with ideas Nd6 or Qxd8 ...Rd8 Be7xf6 afford White the better chances.   9...Ng4  hitting the pawn on h2 and going after the bishop on f3 after  10.h3  Nh2  11.Re1  Nxf3  12.Nxf3  is interesting. However, White's position is easier to play thanks to his lead in development. A sample continuation is  12...Qxd1  13.Rxd1  Bf6  14.Nf4  with the idea Nd5 and Bf4, which can be unpleasant for Black to face in a practical game. }
10. Nc4
{ White intends to grab the bishop pair. Even though the pawn structure is symmetric and Black has no clear weaknesses, the bishop pair in an open position like this one is a big asset and should confer White a slight advantage. }
10... Qe7 11. Nf4 { With the idea Nd3 to attack Black's bishop once again. }
11... Bxf4 12. Bxf4 Rd8 13. Qe2 Qxe2 14. Bxe2
{ White is slightly for choice due to the bishop pair in a relatively open position with pawns on both sides of the board. }
*

