[White "5. 3...dxe4 Part I"]
[Black "5...Bd6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 Bd6
{ This interesting move was played by the French Defense expert 2600+ GM Andrei Istratescu in a blitz game in 2019. Black's play is quite ambitious: he wants to take advantage of the fact that knight is not on f3 and break in the center with e5 after ...O-O. If Black achieves the e5 break under good conditions, he'll solve the problem of the c8 bishop and immediately equalize. }
6. Ne2
{ 6. Nc3 was played by GM Bogdan-Daniel Deac in the aforementioned blitz game. However, I believe the b1 knight should not be placed on c3. White should take advantage of the fact that Black has played placed the bishop on d6  (as opposed to the more conventional ...Be7)  and route the b1 knight to c4 via d2. }
6... O-O 7. Nd2
{ The knight is coming to c4, where it will hit the bishop on d6 and clamp down on the e5 square, effectively preventing any e5 breaks. }
7... c5 8. Nc4 Nc6 9. c3
{ 9. Nxd6 grabbing the bishop pair immediately is also possible but does not give White an advantage. Reinforcing the d4 pawn with c3 first is slightly more challenging. }
9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Ne5 11. Nxd6 Qxd6 12. Be2
{ We of course preserve the pair of bishops } 12... Rd8 13. O-O b6 14. Bf4 Bb7
15. Qc2
{ Black is objectively equal. White is ever so slightly for choice due to the pair of bishops. This is a long term asset, whose value will increase if the queens are exchanged. White should continue with centralizing the rooks with Rfe1 and Rad1. Vacating the f1 square is a good idea to be able to meet Qd5, attacking g2, with Bf1.  In summary, even though White can get slightly more comfortable positions with the pair of bishops, 5... Bd6 is a good reply to 3. Bd3. }
