1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4
{ We now tackle main line where Black captures on e4. I am not claiming White gets an advantage in every line in this variation if Black plays very precisely. However, what I can guarantee is that you will at least get a more comfortable position with clear plans where you will know exactly what to do. Even in the long forcing lines where Black is objectively fine, we are going to pose as many practical problems as possible. After analyzing these variations thoroughly, I found that 3. Bd3 is much more challenging than I initially thought. Black needs to be aware of several subtleties and know quite a lot of theory to be able to equalize. One false step in one of the critical lines and Black can easily end up in a much worse position. }
4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
{ This position is reminiscent of the Rubinstein variation of the French Defense. In the Rubinstein, Black usually develops his light squared bishop along the b7/c6-h1 diagonal, either by b6+Bb7 or Bd7-c6. By placing our bishop on f3, we prevent said developing scheme. Of course, the knight now cannot occupy the f3 square but it will be well placed on e2. }
5... c5 { This is the most common move in practice. } 6. Ne2
{ Despite the knight not being developed to the traditional f3 square, it still does a good job from e2. It protects the pawn on d4 and in case Black decides to capture it, the knight will be well placed in the center after Nxd4. }
6... cxd4 7. Qxd4
{ In case Black immediately takes on d4  (without first playing ... Nc6)  , White should recapture with the Queen. The reason is that after the queen exchange, the endgame is quite unpleasant for Black.  The alternative   7.Nxd4  is well met by  7...Bc5  !  8.Nb3  Trying to avoid the queen exchange with 8.c3 is met by 8...e5, whilst 8.Be3 is not good in view of 8...Qb6.  8...Qxd1  = Black exchanged queens under much more favorable circumstances compared to 7. Qxd4. White will need to lose a tempo with Bxd1 and the knight on b3 is not as active as on d4. }
7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4
{ This endgame is very unpleasant for Black. The bishop on f3 is extremely powerful, and Black has a hard time developing his queenside pieces. Note that neither Nc6 nor Bd7 are possible &#40the b7 pawn would hang in the latter&#41. On top of that, White has ideas with Nd4-b5-c7/d6, which are not easy for Black to meet. }
8... a6 { Black stops any Nb5 jumps and wants to play Bc5 next. } 9. Nd2
{ Intending to meet ... Bc5 with N4b3. If Black does not play ...Bc5, then Nc4 will follow and Black will have to watch out for Nb6/d6 forks. }
9... Bc5 10. N4b3
{ It is better to bring the d4 knight to b3, so that after ...Ba7 White can immediately play Na5 targeting the b7 pawn  (If N2b3 instead, the knight on d4 would be hanging)  . }
10... Ba7 11. Na5 Nd5 12. O-O
{ White will play c4 next with a clear advantage. } *

