1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4
{ We now tackle the main line where Black captures on e4. I am not claiming White gets an advantage in every line in this variation if Black plays very precisely. However, what I can guarantee is that you will at least get a more comfortable position with clear plans where you will know exactly what to do. Even in the long forcing lines where Black is objectively fine, we are going to pose as many practical problems as possible. After analyzing these variations thoroughly, I found that 3. Bd3 is much more challenging than I initially thought. Black needs to be aware of several subtleties and know quite a lot of theory to be able to equalize. One false step in one of the critical lines and Black can easily end up in a much worse position. }
4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
{ This position is reminiscent of the Rubinstein variation of the French Defense. In the Rubinstein, Black usually develops his light squared bishop along the b7/c6-h1 diagonal, either by b6+Bb7 or Bd7-c6. By placing our bishop on f3, we prevent said developing scheme. Of course, the knight now cannot occupy the f3 square but it will be well placed on e2. }
5... c5 { This is the most common move in practice. } 6. Ne2
{ Despite the knight not being developed to the traditional f3 square, it still does a good job from e2. It protects the pawn on d4 and in case Black decides to capture it, the knight will be well placed in the center after Nxd4. }
6... cxd4 7. Qxd4
{ In case Black immediately takes on d4  (without first playing ... Nc6)  , White should recapture with the Queen. The reason is that after the queen exchange, the endgame is quite unpleasant for Black.  The alternative   7.Nxd4  is well met by  7...Bc5  !  8.Nb3  Trying to avoid the queen exchange with 8.c3 is met by 8...e5, whilst 8.Be3 is not good in view of 8...Qb6.  8...Qxd1  = Black exchanged queens under much more favorable circumstances compared to 7. Qxd4. White will need to lose a tempo with Bxd1 and the knight on b3 is not as active as on d4. }
7... Bd6 { Black tries to avoid the exchange of queens. } 8. Bg5
{ With the idea Bxf6, damaging Black's pawn structure on the kingside. } 8...
O-O 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nbc3
{ White is intending O-O-O on the next turn and will then start an attack on Black's king, whose kingside pawn structure is already severely compromised. Black should play 10...Be7, trying to exchange the queen's right away. }
10... Be7
{ This is the only move that allows Black to stay in the game. Exchanging the queens is a must to avoid a mating attack. }
11. O-O-O
{ 11.Qg4  would actually have been a mistake, as after  11...Kh8  Black is actually slightly better. White cannot easily start an attack with the king stuck on e1. }
11... Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Rd8 13. g4
{ Black is objectively fine but White's position is much easier to play. White is planning to improve his position with Be4 and f2-f4. Black has to be very precise to maintain the balance. }
