{ Black has two bishops against White's two knights, which typically favors the bishops. However, this does not apply to this concrete position due to black's weak pawns on c5 and c6. Furthermore, Black's dark squared bishop is severely restricted by the e5 pawn. Black will have to spend a lot of time to get the e5 pawn and when he does he'll have to surrender one of the bishops. White has a slight but very stable advantage. }
12... Be7 13. Nf4 O-O 14. c4 { Fixing the weak pawn on c5. } 14... Re8 15. Kc2
Bf8 16. Nd3
{ The knight on d3 is very well placed, defending e5 and attacking the pawn on c5. White will bring the rooks to e1 and f1. Then, he'll play Ne4 and capture the c5 pawn with a clear advantage. }
