[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. 3...dxe4 Part I"]
[Black "7...e5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4
{ We now tackle the main line where Black captures on e4. I am not claiming White gets an advantage in every line in this variation if Black plays very precisely. However, what I can guarantee is that you will at least get a more comfortable position with clear plans where you will know exactly what to do. Even in the long forcing lines where Black is objectively fine, we are going to pose as many practical problems as possible. After analyzing these variations thoroughly, I found that 3. Bd3 is much more challenging than I initially thought. Black needs to be aware of several subtleties and know quite a lot of theory to be able to equalize. One false step in one of the critical lines and Black can easily end up in a much worse position. }
4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
{ This position is reminiscent of the Rubinstein variation of the French Defense. In the Rubinstein, Black usually develops his light squared bishop along the b7/c6-h1 diagonal, either by b6+Bb7 or Bd7-c6. By placing our bishop on f3, we prevent said developing scheme. Of course, the knight now cannot occupy the f3 square but it will be well placed on e2. }
5... c5 { This is the most common move in practice. } 6. Ne2
{ Despite the knight not being developed to the traditional f3 square, it still does a good job from e2. It protects the pawn on d4 and in case Black decides to capture it, the knight will be well placed in the center after Nxd4. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 { White develops the bishop and protects the pawn on d4. } 7...
e5 { White wins a pawn with } 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. dxe5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Ng4 11. Nd2
Nxe3+ 12. fxe3
{ Black has two bishops against White's two knights, which typically favors the bishops. However, this does not apply to this concrete position due to black's weak pawns on c5 and c6. Furthermore, Black's dark squared bishop is severely restricted by the e5 pawn. Black will have to spend a lot of time to get the e5 pawn and when he does he'll have to surrender one of the bishops. White has a slight but very stable advantage. Here are a few sample continuations: }
12... g6
{ Developing the bishop to g7 makes more sense than playing Be7, as from g7 the bishop will attack the e5 pawn. }
13. Nf4 Bg7 14. Nd3
{ The knight is extremely well placed on d3, defending the e5 pawn and attacking the c5 one. White can continue with c4, Rf1 and then play Ne4 to target the c5 pawn. }
14... O-O 15. Rf1 Re8 16. Rf4
{ This excellent move preserves the pawn on e5 and with it a slight advantage.  The point is that after Bxe5, White will play Re4 and pin Black's bishop:   16...Bxe5  17.Re4  f6  18.Nxe5  Rxe5  19.Rxe5  fxe5  20.Ke2  +− Black cannot protect both the c5 or e5 pawns since they are on dark squares  (and Black no longer has a dark square bishop)  . White is already winning.  If you'd like to train this clickable variation please choose to learn the next variation, which I've marked as an alternative. This is because at the time of writing this course, it is not possible to train subvariations on Chessable and more ambitious/higher rated players might want to train a few more moves. }
*

