4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
{ This position is reminiscent of the Rubinstein variation of the French Defense. In the Rubinstein, Black usually develops his light squared bishop along the b7/c6-h1 diagonal, either by b6+Bb7 or Bd7-c6. By placing our bishop on f3, we prevent said developing scheme. Of course, the knight now cannot occupy the f3 square but it will be well placed on e2. }
5... c5 { This is the most common move in practice. } 6. Ne2
{ Despite the knight not being developed to the traditional f3 square, it still does a good job from e2. It protects the pawn on d4 and in case Black decides to capture it, the knight will be well placed in the center after Nxd4. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 { White develops the bishop and protects the pawn on d4. } 7...
Nd5
