11. Rxd1
{ Nb5 is coming next. White is up a clean pawn with a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. 3...dxe4 Part I"]
[Black "7...Nd5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 Nd5 8.
Bxd5 Qxd5 9. Nbc3 Qh5 { Moving the queen to h5 is also no good. } 10. Nb5
{ White immediately pounces with Nb5, threatening a deadly fork with Nc7. }
10... cxd4
{ This is Black's best try.   10...Rb8  was tried in a rapid game against MVL, which is annotated in the  (model games chapter.)  White can get a decisive advantage by striking in the center with  11.d5  !  11...exd5  12.Nc7  Kd8  13.Nxd5  +- White is already winning with threats like Nf6+ and Bf4. }
11. Nc7+
{ Now comes a forced line where Black's king will be forced into the middle of the board. }
11... Ke7 12. Bf4 { Removing the bishop to safety and threatening Nxa8. } 12...
Rb8 13. Nxd4
{ Attacking the queen on h5 and the knight on c6. Black is forced to trade queens. }
13... Qxd1+ 14. Rxd1 e5 15. Nxc6+ bxc6 16. Bxe5
{ White is now threatening Nd5+ and Bxb8, picking up the rook on b8. } 16...
Rb7 17. Bd6+ Kf6 18. O-O Rxb2 19. Rfe1 { Threatening Be5+ and Bxb2. } 19...
Bxd6 20. Rxd6+ Kg5 21. Rxc6
{ The engines only gives White a slight advantage, but with such an exposed king on g5 Black's position is very hard to play in a practical game. White is threatening h4+ ...Kxh4 and Rc5, when Black's king will be in a mating net. }
