[Black "7...Nd5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4
{ We now tackle the main line where Black captures on e4. I am not claiming White gets an advantage in every line in this variation if Black plays very precisely. However, what I can guarantee is that you will at the very least get a more comfortable position with clear plans where you will know exactly what to do. Even in the long forcing lines where Black is objectively fine, we are going to pose as many practical problems as possible. After analyzing these variations thoroughly, I found that 3. Bd3 is much more challenging than I initially thought. Black needs to be aware of several subtleties and know quite a lot of theory to be able to equalize. One false step in one of the critical lines and Black can easily end up in a much worse position. }
4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
{ This position is reminiscent of the Rubinstein variation of the French Defense. In the Rubinstein, Black usually develops his light squared bishop along the b7/c6-h1 diagonal, either by b6+Bb7 or Bd7-c6. By placing our bishop on f3, we prevent said developing scheme. Of course, the knight now cannot occupy the f3 square but it will be well placed on e2. }
5... c5 { This is the most common move in practice. } 6. Ne2
{ Despite the knight not being developed to the traditional f3 square, it still does a good job from e2. It protects the pawn on d4 and in case Black decides to capture it, the knight will be well placed in the center after Nxd4. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 { White develops the bishop and protects the pawn on d4. } 7...
Nd5
{ Several sources claim this move is mistake. However, after thoroughly analyzing the ensuing lines, I found that Black can reach a dynamically equal position with precise play  (he needs to know 20 moves of theory though !)  . }
8. Bxd5 Qxd5 9. Nbc3
{ White ignores Black's Qxg2 'threat' and simply develops with tempo. } 9...
Qxg2 10. Rg1 Qf3 11. Nb5
{ With the threat of Nc7+. This position was reached in the high profile blitz game between Vladimir Kramnik and Fabiano Caruana at the Norway Masters blitz tournament in 2017 &#40see themodel games chapter for annotations&#41. The game continued: }
11... Rb8 12. dxc5 Bd7
{ Here Kramnik played 13. Nc7+, which is still winning. He actually ended up loosing the blitz game after blundering later on. Stronger would have been }
13. Qd3
{ With multiple threats:   1. Bg5, attacking the queen on f3 and threatening Nc7 checkmate.   2. Nc7+ followed by Bg5+  (after Kd8)  and Qxf3, winning the queen   3. O-O-O, attacking the bishop on d7. Black is defenseless versus this multitude of threats. }
13... Rc8 { Trying to cover the c7 square. } 14. O-O-O
{ Hitting the d7 bishop. } 14... Qd5 15. Qxd5 exd5 16. Rxd5
{ With the idea Nd6+ next. White is already a up a pawn, has developed all his pieces and Black's king is still in the center of the board. White is winning. }
*

