[Black "7...Nd5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 Nd5
{ Several sources claim this move is mistake. However, after thoroughly analyzing the ensuing lines, I found that Black can reach a dynamically equal position with precise play  (he needs to know 20 moves of theory though !)  . }
8. Bxd5 Qxd5 9. Nbc3
{ White ignores Black's Qxg2 'threat' and simply develops with tempo. } 9...
Qxg2 10. Rg1 Qxh2 11. Bf4 Qh3 12. Nb5
{ Several authors stopped here and claimed White was winning since Nc7+ is unstoppable. However, this is the just the start of a very forcing line, where Black can reach a dynamically equal position if he plays with engine-like precision. }
12... f6 { Black vacates the f7 square for his king. } 13. Nc7+
{ The alternative   13.d5  is strongly met by  13...Nd4  14.Nexd4  cxd4  White should now play 15. Qxd4 but Black is fine after 15...Kf7. Going after the rook on a8 with  15.Nc7  would be a big mistake.  15...Kf7  16.Nxa8  Bb4  17.Bd2  The only way to block the check.  17...exd5  Rook e8 is coming and White's king is stuck on e1.  18.Nc7  Trying to cover the e8 square drops a piece to  18...Qh2  -+ With a double-attack on the rook g1 and the knight on c7. Black is winning. }
13... Kf7 14. Nxa8 { White is up a rook but we are only getting started. }
14... cxd4
{ White now has two options:  Option 1:   15. Nxd4. Black still needs to be somewhat precise. The final position is unclear  (hence not a draw)  but I'd rather be White.  Option 2:   15. Nc7+ requires Black  (and White)  to play several only moves but is a draw with best play. I've marked this line as an alternative.   I'll let you decide which variation you prefer. }
*

