1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5
{ This is the most common move in practice. } 6. Ne2
{ Despite the knight not being developed to the traditional f3 square, it still does a good job from e2. It protects the pawn on d4 and in case Black decides to capture it, the knight will be well placed in the center after Nxd4. }
6... Nc6 7. Be3 Nd5
{ Several sources claim this move is mistake. However, after thoroughly analyzing the ensuing lines, I found that Black can reach a dynamically equal position with precise play  (he needs to know 20 moves of theory though !)  . }
8. Bxd5 Qxd5 9. Nbc3
{ White ignores Black's Qxg2 'threat' and simply develops with tempo. } 9...
Qxg2 10. Rg1 Qxh2 11. Bf4 Qh3 12. Nb5
{ Several authors stopped here and claimed White was winning since Nc7+ is unstoppable. However, this is the just the start of a very forcing line, where Black can reach a dynamically equal position if he plays with engine-like precision. }
12... f6 { Black vacates the f7 square for his king. } 13. Nc7+ Kf7 14. Nxa8
{ White is up a rook but we are only getting started. } 14... cxd4
{ White now has two options:   Option 1:   15. Nxd4. Black still needs to be somewhat precise. The final position is unclear  (hence not a draw)  but I'd rather be White. I'll let you decide which variation you prefer.  Option 2:   15. Nc7 requires Black  (and White)  to play several only moves but leads to a draw with best play. I've marked this line as an alternative. }
15. Nc7
{ The more forcing option. Black will have to find several only moves to keep the balance but he can get a draw basically by force. Warning: White also needs to be precise. }
15... Bb4+ 16. Bd2 Ne5 { Black is threatening checkmate with Nf3. } 17. Ng3
{ White covers the f3 square and is now threatening to capture the bishop on b4. }
17... Bxd2+ 18. Kxd2
{ 18.Qxd2  is a blunder because it allows the royal fork  18...Nf3+  winning the queen and the game. }
18... Qh6+ 19. Ke2 Bd7
{ The best move covering the b5 retreat square for White's knight. Black wants to follow up with Rc8 and capture the knight on c7. }
20. Qxd4
{ Trying to create a retreat square for the knight on b5 with   20.a4  is a mistake on account of the following forcing line  20...Rc8  21.Nb5  Rxc2  This tactical shot is the reason 20.a4 does not work.  22.Qxc2  d3  This is the point. White loses the queen and the game.  23.Qxd3  Nxd3  24.Kxd3  Qf4  -+ The king on d3 is too exposed. White's two rooks are no match against Black's queen and bishop. Black is winning. }
20... Rc8 { The c7 knight has nowhere to go. } 21. f4
{ The most critical move. Black now needs to find the following sequence to keep the balance. }
21... Qh2+ 22. Kd1 Rxc7 23. fxe5 Bb5
{ Another only move, threatening to win the queen with Rd7.   The natural recapture   23...Qxc2  is a blunder as after  24.Ke1  Black ran out of checks/ threats and White's extra rook will decide the game. }
24. Ke1 Rxc2 { Black is now threatening ...Re2+, Nxe2 and ...Qxe2 checkmate. }
25. Qe3 { White covers the e2 square. } 25... Qh4
{ This retreating move is very strong. Black is threatening a devastating check on b4. }
26. Rd1 { White brings the rook to d1 to meet Qb4+ with Rd2. } 26... Re2+ 27.
Qxe2 Bxe2 28. Kxe2 f5 29. Rd7+ Kf8 30. Rxb7
{ White has two rooks and a knight vs the queen but is 3 pawns down. With such an exposed king on e2, White can never be better. In fact, White should force a draw immediately by bringing the g1 rook to the 7th rank. For instance: }
30... g5 31. Rh1
{ White is threatening Rxh7, after which Black's king would be in a mating net. Black cannot allow this so he forces a perpetual. }
31... Qc4+ 32. Ke1 Qc1+ 33. Ke2 Qc4+ 34. Ke1 Qc1+ { Draw. } *

