1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5
{ 8...Nxd4  9.Qxd4  As we've seen before, recapturing with the queen is much stronger than Bxd4. The resulting endgame after the queen exchange is quite unpleasant for Black.  9...Qxd4  10.Bxd4±  White will continue with O-O and Nc3-b5 with a clear edge. }
9. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we are going to cover all of Black's alternatives on move 9, that is 9... Be7, 9... Bb4, and 9... Nxf3. The main line, 9... a6, is covered in the next chapter. }
9... Bb4
{ Black wants to capture on c3, ruining White's queenside pawn structure. } 10.
Nb5
{ White protects the knight on c3 and is planning to play a3, hitting the bishop on b4. }
10... a6 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. O-O-O+
{ White brings the rook into the game with tempo. } 12... Ke7 13. a3
{ This is a strong intermezzo. } 13... axb5
{ 13...Bxc3  Blunders checkmate in 2.  14.Bc5  Ke8  15.Nc7  Checkmate. } 14.
axb4 Ra1+ 15. Nb1 Nxf3 16. Bc5+ { Another nice intermezzo. } 16... Ke8 17. gxf3
{ With the idea b3 and Kb2, kicking the rook back, and then Nc3, attacking the pawn on b5. White should also play Rhg1 to attack the g7 pawn. Even though Black is objectively fine, White's position is easier to play. The bishop on c5 is very strong and Black's king is stuck in the center, which means the rook on h8 is also out of the game. }
