1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we are going to cover of all Black's alternatives on move 9, that is 9... Be7, 9... Bb4 and 9... Nxf3. The main line, 9... a6, is covered in the next chapter. }
9... Bb4
{ Black wants to capture on c3, ruining White's queenside pawn structure. } 10.
Nb5
{ White protects the knight on c3 and is planning to play a3, hitting the bishop on b4. }
10... Qa5
{ Black is threatening Qxb5 taking advantage of the fact that the knight on c3 is pinned. }
11. O-O { White deals with Qxb5 by simply moving the king to safety. } 11...
Nxf3+
{ 11...O-O  is likely to transpose to the main line  12.a3  N This novelty improves over ½-½ Safarli,E  (2653)  -Erigaisi,A  (2481)  2018  12...Bxc3  13.Nxc3  Rd8  14.Qe2  Black's best is to play ...Nxf3 now, leading to very similar play as the main line. If instead  14...Qc7  protecting the b7 pawn to develop the bishop on c8, White can get a clear edge after  15.Bf4  Nxf3  16.Qxf3  Qe7  17.Bg5  ± With a very annoying pin. White can increase the pressure with Ne4, whilst Black still hasn't solved the problem of the bishop on c8. }
12. Qxf3 O-O 13. a3
{ Practically forcing Black to part with the pair of bishops. } 13... Bxc3
{ Retreating with   13...Be7  is no good as after  14.Rad1  White is suddenly threatening b4 ...Qa6 Nc7, picking up the rook. Black should thus play  14...Bd7  . And now White has the fantastic  15.Rxd7  !  15...Nxd7  16.Qxb7  Rfd8  17.b4  . Black's queen is suddenly trapped, so  17...Bxb4  is forced:  18.axb4  Qxb4  19.Rb1  Qc4  20.Bxa7  ± White has two pieces for a rook, which is a clear advantage. }
14. Nxc3
{ White has a small edge in this position since Black's light-squared bishop is still stuck on c8. Stockfish is already recommending Black to give up the b7 pawn with 14... Bd7 and thus White is clearly for choice. }
