{ Has only been played a couple of times but is one of Black's best tries against 3. Bd3. I was not able to find a way to put any pressure on Black's position &#40if you have any ideas, please let me know and I'll update the course&#41.   Black is threatening to take the knight on b5 &#40note that the c3 knight is pinned&#41. }
11. a3 { 11.Qd4  is analyzed in analternative line. } 11... Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3
Bxc3+ 13. Nxc3 Bc6
{ Black has managed to exchange several pieces and solved the problem of the c8 bishop. }
14. Qg3 O-O 15. f3
{ This position is a tad drawish due to the presence of opposite-colored bishops. Neither side has any real weaknesses. }
15... Nd5 16. Rd1
{ White brings the rook into the game, lining it up against Black's queen. }
16... Qf6 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Rd4
{ White can continue with Kf2 and Rhd1. We can also consider pushing the h-pawn down the board to create threats against the Black king. When Black puts a rook on c8, White can simply play c3.   The position is equal &#40but not drawn, so White can still outplay his opponent&#41.   In summary, 3... dxe4 10... Bd7 is a good equalizing attempt for Black. }
