1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3 Bb4 10. Nb5 Bd7 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. Nxc3 Bc6
{ Black is trying to exchange as many pieces as possible. NM Bryan Tills and GM Alex Lenderman in the Chessable course Master the French Defense assessed Black was equal after Bc6. Let's analyze it a bit more: }
13. Qxd8+ Rxd8 14. Bxc6+ Nxc6 15. h3 { Stopping annoying jumps like Ng4. }
15... b6 { Black prepares Ke7. With ...b6, Black cuts out the annoying Bc5+. }
16. Rd1 Ke7
{ 16...Rxd1  17.Kxd1  Ke7  18.Ke2  leads to almost the same position as the text. }
17. Ke2
{ Without queens, the kings are much more active in the center of the board. }
17... Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Rd8 19. Rxd8 Kxd8 20. b4
{ Black is objectively equal. However, this is far from a draw. White has two small advantages:    (1)  With pawns on both sides of the board, White's bishop is stronger than Black's knight.    (2)  White has a 3 vs 2 majority on the queenside, which makes it easier to create a passed pawn  (compared to Black's 4 vs 3 on the kingside)  .   Thus, White can basically play this position for two results. Black has virtually no winning chances and needs to be precise to hold. }
