Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3 Bb4 10. Nb5 Bd7 11. a3 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 Bxc3+ 13. Nxc3 Qc7
{ Even though this move is not that relevant from a theoretical perspective, it was played by GM Arun Prasad in 2015 and should thus be covered for completeness sake. }
14. Bf4
{ Improving the position of the bishop with a tempo.  For the endgame lovers out there   14.Qg3  is also an interesting try for a small advantage.  14...Qxg3  15.hxg3  Bc6  16.f3  a6  17.O-O-O  = This a more pleasant endgame for White. Don't assume it's a dead draw due to the opposite-colored bishops. White has a 3 vs 2 on the queenside and hence it's easier for him to create a passed pawn  (compared to Black's 4 vs 3 on the kingside)  . Furthermore, the open h-file is very useful to lift a rook to the queenside, e.g. Rh4-b4 later in the game. The 3.Bd3 specialist GM Vladimir Onischuk  (2629)  managed to beat GM Arun Prasad  (2502)  from this position in 2015. }
14... Qb6 15. O-O-O Bc6 16. Qe2 O-O 17. Be5
{ The kings are castled on opposite sides but White's slightly better placed pieces give him the better prospects. White is now threatening Bxf6 and can follow up with Rhe1 and Qg4  (once the Nf6 moves away)  .  Based on beta tester feedback and because Chessable has a wide audience, I've decided to mark the following line that illustrates how play is likely to continue as an alternative variation. Ambitious and/or higher-rated players can choose to train the next alternative variation if they see fit. }
