1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3 Bb4 10. Nb5 Bd7 11. Qd4
{ This is an interesting alternative to 11. a3, which is covered in the9...Bb4 #5-7 variations.  White attacks Black's knight and bishop, which forces Black's hand. }
11... Bxc3+ 12. Nxc3 Nxf3+ 13. gxf3
{ White is now ready to castle queenside. The opening of the g-file will allow us to attack the g7 pawn with Rg1 and make it hard for Black to castle kingside. }
13... Bc6
{ 13...O-O?!  is a mistake. Black castles into a big attack.  14.Rg1  Bc6  15.Qe5  White can continue with Rd1 and Bd4 with a clear advantage. Note that if  15...Qb8?  16.Rxg7!  is already winning  16...Kxg7  17.Qg5  Kh8  18.Qxf6  Kg8  19.Bd4+−  And Black gets mated. }
14. Qe5 { Centralizing the queen and avoiding exchanges. } 14... Bxf3 15. Rg1
{ Moving the rook out of danger and attacking the g7 pawn. } 15... Qb8 16. Qb5+
{ Check! This forces Black's knight back. } 16... Nd7 17. Rg3
{ It's now time to kick the bishop back, which was stopping us from castling queenside. }
17... Bc6 18. Qb4 { A good square for the queen, stopping ...O-O. } 18... a5
19. Qh4 Qd8 20. Qg4
{ Attacking the pawn on g7, which had been hanging for several moves. } 20...
g6 21. O-O-O
{ White is a pawn down but has excellent compensation. Black's king is stuck in the middle of the board and there are numerous dark-squared weaknesses in his camp.  The engines slightly prefer White's position, which I also find much easier to play. The pawn advance h4-h5 is in the cards. }
