1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5
{ 8...Nxd4  9.Qxd4  As we've seen before, recapturing with the queen is much stronger than Bxd4. The resulting endgame after the queen exchange is quite unpleasant for Black.  9...Qxd4  10.Bxd4  &plusmn  White will continue with 0-0 and Nc3-b5 with a clear edge. }
9. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we are going to cover all of Black's alternatives on move 9, that is 9... Be7, 9... Bb4, and 9... Nxf3. The main line, 9... a6, is covered in the next chapter. }
9... Bb4
{ Black wants to capture on c3, ruining White's queenside pawn structure. } 10.
Nb5 Nxf3+ { Capturing the knight on f3 right away is also possible. } 11. Qxf3
O-O 12. a3 { Time to get rid of Black's bishop. } 12... Bxc3+
{ 12...Be7?  drops the a7 pawn to  13.Bxa7± } 13. Nxc3 Bd7
{ We have been following the game ½-½ Sousa, A.  2405  - Thybo, J.  2479  2017 where White played 14.Bg5. Even better is }
14. O-O-O
{ pinning the bishop and thus stopping Bc6.   Note that  14.Qxb7  is not such a good idea on account of  14...Rb8  15.Qxa7  Rxb2  16.O-O  Rxc2=  when material equality has been restored and White has no advantage. }
14... Qc7 15. Bf4
{ Improving the position of the bishop, which is heading to the e5 square. From e5, it will eye both flanks of the board and exert significant pressure on Black's kingside. }
15... Qc6
{ Worse is   15...Qb6?!  when White can immediately pressure the knight on f6 with  16.Be5!  Bc6  17.Qg3  Ne8  18.Bd4!  Qc7  19.Bc5±  when Black's rook on f8 is trapped. }
16. Qd3 Rfd8 { And now } 17. h4
{ is very interesting. White intends to follow up with Be5 and Qg3, with an attack on Black's king. Black, on the other hand, can hardly reach our king on c1. White should later consider marching the h-pawn down the board to create weaknesses in Black's kingside. }
