{ This move was not covered in the GM Repertoire on the French Defense Vol. 3 published by Quality Chess in 2015. The author, GM Emanuel Berg, only considered 11. O-O. White is threatening Nxe6 with a discovered attack on Black's queen. }
11... Bd7 12. Bxb7 Rb8 13. Bf4 { This is the point behind Bxb7. } 13... Rxb7
14. Bxe5 Qb6 15. Nb3
{ White is a pawn up and will neutralize Black's attack with moves like Qe3, Bd4 and Rd3. By centralizing all his pieces, White will make it very difficult for Black to create any sort of attack. Black does have some compensation so White also needs to tread carefully. Here is a sample continuation: }
15... Rc8
{ 15...a5  is well met by  16.Qe3  and Black is basically forced to exchange the queens on e3. }
16. Bd4 Qc7 17. Rd3
{ White overprotects the knight on c3 and is ready to bring the other rook into the game with Rhd1. }
17... a5 18. Rhd1 Bc6 19. Qe5
{ Black cannot avoid the queen exchange and White is still a pawn up.  Note that   19...Qxe5  20.Bxe5  Bxg2  fails to win back the pawn for Black as the a-pawn drops at the end  21.Rg1  Bc6  22.Nxa5  ± with three  (!)  connected passed pawns on the queenside. }
