1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we are going to cover of all Black's alternatives on move 9, that is 9... Be7, 9... Bb4 and 9... Nxf3. The main line, 9... a6, is covered in the next chapter. }
9... Be7 10. Qe2 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 O-O
{ Securing the king is Black's most logical move.   11...Qa5  has been played OTB but it is not a good move. It can be met with the stunning  12.Nc6  the point being that after  12...Qh5  13.Qxh5  Nxh5  14.Nxe7  Kxe7  and now the strong  15.g4  Nf6  16.Bc5  Ke8  17.Nb5  +- leaves White with a decisive advantage. Black has no satisfactory reply to threats of Nc7 and Nd6+.   11...Bb4  has also been played in the past but can be met with  12.O-O-O  with the point that after  12...Bxc3  White once again has the fantastic  13.Nc6  hitting the queen and threatening Rd8+  13...Qc7  14.Rd8  Qxd8  15.Nxd8  +- gives White a decisive material advantage. }
12. O-O-O
{ White has completed his development and will play g4 next. The kings are castled on opposite sides so White should start an attack against Black's king. }
12... Qa5
{ Getting the queen out of the d-file is advisable. From a5, the queen puts some pressure on the a2 pawn and can also easily swing to the kingside. }
13. g4
{ White starts an attack on Black's king by pushing the g-pawn. Black does not have any counterplay. }
13... Nd7
{ Black wants to play Ne5-c4.  Note that   13...Nd5  is met by the typical tactic  14.Nf5  !  Re8  15.Nxd5  exd5  16.Rxd5  ± White is a pawn up. }
14. Nb3
{ This is an improvement over 14. h4, which was played in the game 0-1  (44)  Eizaguerri Floris,M  (2082)  -Pert,R  (2423)  London 2016. }
14... Qa6 15. Rhg1 Ne5 16. Qe4
{ f4-f5 is coming with a big attack. Black is in trouble. } *

