[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Qe2 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 O-O 12. O-O-O Qc7
{ This move is inferior to 12...Qa5 and is not theoretically relevant. Thus, there is no point in drilling this line and as such I've made it an informational variation. Nevertheless, it was played in a blitz game by GM Rasmus Svane so it should be covered for completeness sake. }
13. Ndb5 Qa5 14. a3
{ Very precise! White intends to play Bf4 and Bc7 without allowing Black's queen to go to the b4 square.   This point becomes clearer if we consider the immediate  14.Bf4  a6  15.Bc7  Qb4  This is the square we want to take away and the main point behind 14.a3 }
14... Bd7 { Trying to get rid of the knight on b5. } 15. Rxd7
{ A very nice tactical shot! } 15... Nxd7 16. Qxb7
{ This is the point. The Nd7 and the Be7 are both loose  (and loose pieces drop off!)  . }
16... Bf6
{ This is a mistake.   Much better was  16. ..Rfd8  17.Rd1  leading to a position where  17...Rab8  Qxa7  Qxa7  19.Bxa7  Ra8  20.a4  even though White is technically down an exchange, his passed pawns on the queenside coupled with the activity of his pieces actually give him the advantage. }
17. Qxd7 { White now has two pieces for a the rook and a decisive advantage. }
17... Rfd8 18. Qb7 Rab8
{ We have been following the game ½-½  @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Gunnarsson,J @@StartBracket@@2450@@EndBracket@@ - Svane,R @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2017. Now }
19. Qxa7 { would have decided the game on the spot. } 19... Rxb5 20. Qxa5 Rxa5
21. Bb6
{ White will get the exchange back and end up with two extra pawns, which are actually protected passed pawns. White thus has a decisive advantage. }
