[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. 3...dxe4 Part III Main Line"]
[Black "9...a6 10...Nxf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3 a6 { This is the main move in the 3... dxe4 variation. } 10.
Qe2 Nxf3+ 11. gxf3
{ I first came across this unusual recapture when it was recommended by GM Avetik Grigoryan in a video series. In this course, I have significantly expanded on the already excellent analysis he provided.   At low depth, the engine thinks Black is actually better but the longer you let it run, the more it starts liking White's position. This unexpected move is very strong and will likely come as surprise to many of your opponents. For instance, GM Romain Edouard in his French Repertoire video series on chess24 doesn't even cover 11. gxf3. In fact, it has only be played a handful of times over the board according to my databases.  The idea behind 11. gxf3 is to use White's considerable lead in development to seize the initiative. Capturing with the g-pawn opens up the g-file for White's rook and after O-O-O, White is ready to attack Black's king. The alternative would be recapturing on f3 with the knight or the queen, but such a slow approach allows Black to easily equalize.     The natural recapture  11.Qxf3  is well met by  11...e5  12.Nf5?!  Qa5⩱  Black is threatening e4 and is already slightly better. The alternative retreat  12.Nb3=  is better but fails to give White an advantage. It is covered in the 11.Qxf3 alternative variation. }
11... Nd5 12. Nxd5
{ White eliminates Black's only active piece and is ready to castle long on the next turn. }
12... Qxd5 13. O-O-O
{ White has 4 pieces already in the game whilst Black has only developed his queen. Black needs to be very careful not to lose immediately. }
13... Be7
{ Another good option is  13...Bd7  with ideas of ...Qxa2 and ...Bb5. We can sidestep all of this with  14.Kb1  a sample continuation being  14...Be7  15.Bf4  Bb5   15...Bf6  can be met with  16.Qe3  Bc6  17.Nxc6  Qxc6  18.Rd6=  with good play.  16.Nxb5  Qxb5  17.Qxb5  axb5  18.Rd3=  This endgame is objectively balanced but there is still ample room to play for the full point. }
14. Rhg1 { Activating the rook and hitting the pawn on g7. } 14... Bf6 15. Nb3
{ Stopping ...Qxa2 and hitting the queen on d5. } 15... Qe5 16. c3
{ Stopping Qxb2 and blunting the bishop on f6. } 16... Qb5
{ We have been following the game Gordievsky,D  (2555)  -Schekachikhin,M  (2347)  St Petersburg 2016. White played Qxb5 and went on to win the resulting endgame. Stronger would have been: }
17. c4
{ White has a big lead in development and so he should not exchange queens. }
17... Qh5 18. Bc5
{ Stopping Black from securing his king with O-O. White can continue with Bd6 and even Rd5  (the e-pawn is pinned)  with a big initiative. }
