1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3 a6 10. Qe2 Nxf3+ 11. gxf3
{ I first came across this unusual recapture when it was recommended by GM Avetik Grigoryan in a video series. In this course, I have significantly expanded on the already excellent analysis he provided.   At low depth, the engine thinks Black is actually better but the longer you let it run, the more it starts liking White's position. This unexpected move is very strong and will likely come as surprise to many of your opponents. For instance, GM Romain Edouard in his French Repertoire video series on chess24 doesn't even cover 11. gxf3. In fact, it has only be played a handful of times over the board according to my databases.  The idea behind 11. gxf3 is to use White's considerable lead in development to seize the initiative. Capturing with the g-pawn opens up the g-file for White's rook and after O-O-O, White is ready to attack Black's king. The alternative would be recapturing on f3 with the knight or the queen, but such a slow approach allows Black to easily equalize.     The natural recapture  11.Qxf3  is well met by  11...e5  12.Nf5?!  Qa5⩱  Black is threatening e4 and is already slightly better. The alternative retreat  12.Nb3=  is better but fails to give White an advantage. It is covered in the 11.Qxf3 alternative variation. }
11... Nd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. O-O-O Qxa2
{ Taking this pawn when Black hasn't developed any pieces is incredibly risky. Black has to be extremely precise not to lose immediately }
14. Nb3 { Stopping Qa1+. } 14... Be7
{ 14...Bd7  is strongly met by the exchange sacrifice  15.Rxd7!  After  15...Kxd7  16.Qc4  Ke8  17.f4  gives White a decisive advantage with f5 coming next. To avoid losing immediately, Black should play  17...Ba3  and after  18.bxa3  Qxa3  19.Kb1+−  White has an overwhelming position. Next up is Rg1 when Black's rooks are merely spectators. }
15. Rhg1
{ Activating the rook with a tempo on the pawn on g7. For example, if Black goes astray with }
15... Bf6
{ White can get a big advantage after   15...g6  A very precise engine move that I doubt any human would find as it weakens the kingside and opens the d4-h8 diagonal.  16.Bd4  16...f6  17.f4  ⩲ Black's king is still stuck in the center of the board, the queen on a2 is offside, and the bishop is still stuck on c8. The engines assess this as slightly better for White  (and Black needs to be very precise not to end up clearly worse)  . White has the initiative and should continue with h4-h5 to blast open the g-file. }
16. Bd4 Bd7
{ Also no good is   16...Bxd4  17.Rxd4  g6  18.Qe4  White is suddenly threatening to trap the queen on a2 with Ra4!  18...Bd7  Practically forced.  19.Rxd7!  A beautiful shot that wins the game on the spot.  19...Kxd7  20.Qxb7+  If Black goes back to 8th rank, the a8 rook drops with check and if he steps forward with  20...Kd6  he gets mated after  21.Rd1+  Ke5  22.Qe7!  White is threatening mate in 2 with the stunning Rd5!  22...Rhe8  23.Rd5+  Kxd5  24.Qc5  A beautiful way to end the game! }
17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Qe3
{ Black's king is stuck in the center of the board. White has multiple threats including Rg7 and Qc3, with a clear advantage. }
