10. Qe2 Nxf3+ 11. gxf3
{ I first came across this unusual recapture when it was recommended by GM Avetik Grigoryan in a video series. In this course, I have significantly expanded on the already excellent analysis he provided.   At low depth, the engine thinks Black is actually better but the longer you let it run, the more it starts liking White's position. This unexpected move is very strong and will likely come as surprise to many of your opponents. For instance, GM Romain Edouard in his French Repertoire video series on chess24 doesn't even cover 11. gxf3. In fact, it has only be played a handful of times over the board according to my databases.  The idea behind 11. gxf3 is to use White's considerable lead in development to seize the initiative. Capturing with the g-pawn opens up the g-file for White's rook and after O-O-O, White is ready to attack Black's king. The alternative would be recapturing on f3 with the knight or the queen, but such a slow approach allows Black to easily equalize.     The natural recapture  11.Qxf3  is well met by  11...e5  12.Nf5?!  Qa5⩱  Black is threatening e4 and is already slightly better. The alternative retreat  12.Nb3=  is better but fails to give White an advantage. It is covered in the 11.Qxf3 alternative variation. }
11... Qc7 { This novelty is Black's best try. } 12. O-O-O b5 13. Rhg1
{ The rook on g1 eyes the g7 pawn and stops Black from playing Be7. } 13... Bb7
14. Nf5
{ A very strong move, hitting the pawn on g7 Even though Black is objectively fine, it will be very hard for him to find the correct defense/ sequence of only moves to keep the balance over the board. Thus, if you are well prepared, you can score a lot of points from this position. }
14... b4 15. Na4 { This knight on the rim is far from dim. } 15... Rc8
{ This is the only move that holds the balance. Black is now threatening Bxf3, taking advantage of the fact that Qxf3 is not possible due to Qxc2 checkmate. }
16. Rd2
{ The most challenging continuation. This move poses Black some practical problems. Beware, you should also know these variations well if you want to enter these complications!    If you want to avoid the complications after 16. Rd2, you can play   16.Nc5  This move leads to a threefold repetition after  16...Bxc5  17.Nxg7  Ke7  18.Nf5  Ke8  19.Ng7  Draw. }
16... Qa5 17. Nb6 Qxa2
{ Black is suddenly threatening checkmate but no worries, Stockfish has got your back.   17...Qxf5  18.Nxc8  Bxc8  19.Qc4  Bd7  20.Qc7  +− White is winning since Black is powerless against both Qb8+ and Bb6 followed by Qd8 checkmate. }
18. Rd6 { White vacates the d2 square for his king. The rook on d6 is taboo. }
18... Bxd6 { Capturing the rook is a blunder. } 19. Nxd6+
{ Forking the king and the c8 rook. } 19... Ke7 20. Ndxc8+ Bxc8 21. Bc5+
{ Activating the bishop with tempo. } 21... Kd8 22. Qe5
{ White is threatening Qb8 and Qxc8 checkmate. } 22... Qa1+ 23. Kd2 Qxg1 24.
Qb8
{ 24. h4  (to stop any Qg5 checks)  is forced mate in 15  (!)  but the text is more straightforward and still winning. Black has no defense against Qxc8 checkmate  (he'll have to sacrifice his queen with Qg5+ and Qd5 to avoid checkmate)  . }
