[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. 3...dxe4 Part III Main Line"]
[Black "11.Qxf3 - Simpler (but less ambitious) alternative to 11. gxf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3 a6 { This is the main move in the 3... dxe4 variation. } 10.
Qe2 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3
{ This is an alternative to 11. gxf3 that is especially suitable for lower-rated players  (or if you simply don't want to have to learn as much theory)  as it avoids the complications in the aforementioned variations. However, Black can equalize after this queen capture in straightforward fashion and get a comfortable position.   11.gxf3!  is the most challenging move and my main recommendation. }
11... e5
{ This move is the reason 11. Qxf3 does not give White any advantage. The knight is basically forced to go back. }
12. Nb3
{ A sad retreat. The main issue with White's position is that O-O-O is not possible.   As commented in the previous lines  12.Nf5  Qa5⩱  Black is threatening e4 and is already slightly better. }
12... Bb4 13. Bc5 { White should eliminate Black's active bishop on b4. } 13...
Bxc5 14. Nxc5 O-O 15. O-O Qc7 16. Nd3
{ Centralizing the knight and putting some pressure on the e5 pawn. } 16... Be6
17. Rfe1 { Hitting the pawn on e5, which can be comfortably defended with }
17... Nd7
{ This is a playable position where Black is quite comfortable. It's objectively equal and if you want to avoid the complications/ need to remember lines after 11. gxf3, then 11. Qxf3 is a fully playable alternative.   Here is a sample line of how play might develop  18.Nd5  Bxd5  19.Qxd5  Rfe8  20.Re2  Doubling on the e-file to target the e5 pawn is a sensible plan.  20...Re6  Black follows suit.  21.Rae1  Rae8=  with a balanced position. }
