[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Model games"]
[Black " 1-0 Onischuk,V (2601) -Vusatiuk,V (2344) 2017"]
[Result "*"]

{ This model game in the 3... c5 variation was played between GM Vladimir Onischuk and IM Vladimir Vusatiuk in 2017. Onischuk, a very strong 2600+ GM, is a specialist in the 3.Bd3 variation and here we are going to see how he defeated an IM in only 18 moves. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 c5
{ This transposes to a variation of the Exchange French, where Black will be left with an isolated pawn on d5. This might not be everyone's cup of tea. }
4. exd5 Qxd5
{ This natural recapture is actually a mistake. At first sight, it seems that Black will win a pawn as Qxd5 is a double attack on the d4 and g2 pawns. }
5. Nc3 { White simply ignores Black's threat and develops with tempo. } 5...
Qd8 6. Bf4
{ I recommended 6. Nf3 in the course but the text is also possible. } 6... Nf6
7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qf3
{ White will castle queenside, play Ne2 and then launch an attack on Black's king with Rhg1 and g4-g5. This primitive plan is surprisingly strong and not easy to meet. }
8... O-O 9. O-O-O Qa5 10. Nge2
{ White is fully mobilized and next on the agenda is Rhg1 and g4-g5. On the other hand, Black has yet to develop his queenside pieces and did not last more than 8 moves. }
10... Bd7 11. Rhg1 Bc6 12. Qh3 Nbd7 13. g4
{ White is threatening g5, attacking the knight on f6, and Qxh7. } 13... e5
{ This is a mistake. 13... g6 was necessary. } 14. g5 exf4 15. gxf6 Nxf6 16.
Rxg7+ { This nice tactic ends the game. } 16... Kxg7 17. Rg1+ Kh8 18. Qh6
{ Black resigned since he has no defense against both Qxf6+ and Qg7 checkmate.   1-0  (18)  Onischuk,V  (2601)  -Vusatiuk,V  (2344)  Lutsk 2017 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Model games"]
[Black "1-0 Reinaldo Castineira,R (2466) -Labairu Senosiain,J (1966) 2016"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is one of the very few games that has been played in the3... Nf6 7. a3! variation. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Ne2 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. a3
{ As mentioned in the course, this rare move practically refutes the 3... Nf6 variation. }
7... cxd4
{ This capture does not make much sense as it allows white to develop the b1 knight to the ideal c3 square. }
8. cxd4 Qb6 9. Nbc3 Be7
{ Note that   9...Nxd4  blunders a piece on account of  10.Be3  Bc5  11.Nxd4  Bxd4  12.Na4  This is the point. The queen cannot hold on to the bishop.  12...Qa5  13.b4  Qd8  14.Bxd4  +− White has an extra piece. }
10. Be3 f5
{ Black was afraid that after O-O he would get steamrolled on the kingside with f4-f5. However, ...f5 severely weakens the e6 pawn, which White exploits immediately. }
11. Nf4 { White immediately targets the newly created weakness on e6. } 11...
Nf8 { A sad necessity. There was no other way of protecting the e6 pawn. } 12.
O-O Nd8 13. Rc1 Bd7 14. Ncxd5
{ A nice tactic. White temporarily sacrifices a knight but will regain the material with interest with Nc7+. It is not suprising that such a sacrifice is already winning when all of Black's minor pieces are on the last two ranks of the board. }
14... exd5 15. Nxd5 Qxb2 16. Nc7+ Kf7 17. Nxa8
{ White is an exchange up and had no issues wrapping up the game. } 17... Bxa3
18. Rb1 Qa2 19. Ra1 Qb2 20. d5
{ With the idea e6, forking the king and bishop on d7. } 20... Qxe5 21. Rxa3
{ Black is now down an entire rook and could have already resigned. } 21... Qb8
22. Qh5+ g6 23. Qh4 { With the idea Bd4 followed by Qf6. } 23... Qxa8 24. Bd4
Rg8 25. Qf6+
{ Black resigned as after 25... Ke8 and 26. Bc5 there is no defense against Qe7 checkmate.   1-0  (25)  Reinaldo Castineira, R  (2466)  -Labairu Senosiain,J  (1966)  Navarra 2016 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Model games"]
[Black " 1-0 Onischuk,V (2618) -Harika,D (2509) 2015"]
[Result "*"]

{ This model game is  (almost)  a miniature by GM Onischuk in the3... dxe4 9... Be7 variation. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Qe2 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3
{ 11.gxf3, opening up the g-file and intending to follow up with 0-0-0, was also possible. }
11... O-O 12. O-O-O
{ The kings are castled on opposite sides so White should start an attack against Black's king. Hence, White is going to play g4-g5. }
12... Bd7 13. g4
{ 13.Qxb7  Capturing the pawn is a big mistake. Even though White wins a pawn, he opens the b-file for Black to attack White's king.  13...Rb8  =+ White's king will come under a serious attack. }
13... Qa5 14. g5 Nd5 15. Nf5 { This is a nice tactical shot ! } 15... Nxc3
{ The point is that   15...exf5  drops the Nd5 to  16.Rxd5  Qc7  17.Nb5  ⩲ }
16. Nxe7+ { Check. } 16... Kh8 17. Bd2
{ Perhaps even stronger would have been   17.Rd4  with the idea Rh4, Rxh7 and Qh5 checkmate.  Capturing the knight with   17.bxc3  ? would have been a mistake due to  17...Qa3+  forking the king and the knight on e7.  18.Kb1  Qxe7  ⩱ }
17... Nxa2+ 18. Kb1 Qd8
{ The altenative retreat   18...Qa6  is no good.  19.Qh3  +- Pinning the h7 pawn and threatening g6. Black does not have a good way to counter this. }
19. Bf4
{ Even stronger would have been   19.Qa3  to capture the knight on a2. } 19...
Qxe7 20. Bd6 Qe8 21. Rhe1
{ Capturing the rook on f8 would have been met by Bc6, skewering the Qf3 and the Rh1. Thus, White brings the rook to safety and is now threatening Bxf8. }
21... Rg8 22. Rd4
{ With the ideas Qh5 followed by Rh4 or Rh4-Rxh7 and Qh5 checkmate. } 22... Bc6
{ This move costs Black the game.  Black had to play   22...Qd8  vacating the e8 square to be able to meet  23.Qh5  with  23...Be8 }
23. Qh5 f6 24. g6 h6 25. Bf4 { With the threat Bxh6. } 25... e5 26. Bxh6 Bf3
27. Bxg7+ { A nice way to end the game. Black is busted. } 27... Kxg7 28. Qh7+
Kf8 29. Rd7 Qxd7 30. Qxd7 Rxg6 31. Qf5
{ Black resigned since the bishop on f3, the rook on g6 and the knight on a2 are all hanging.   1-0  (31)  Onischuk,V  (2618)  -Harika,D  (2509)  Abu Dhabi 2015 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Model games"]
[Black " 1-0 Lomasov,S (2540) -Sachdev,T (2400) 2018"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this model game, GM Lomasov with the White pieces gives a textbook demonstration on how to play against Black's bishop pair and attack the weak c5 and c6 pawns in the 3... dxe4 7... e5 variation. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 e5
{ Black tries to immediately liberate his c8 bishop with 7... e5 and is even threatening ...e4. }
8. Bxc6+
{ As we saw in the course, Bxc6 nets White a pawn and damages Black's queenside structure. }
8... bxc6 9. dxe5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Ng4 11. Nd2 Nxe5 12. Re1
{ This idea behind this mysterious rook move is to meet ...Ng4 with Nf4 so that Nxe3 can be met by Rxe3. }
12... Ba6 13. Bf4 Nc4
{ As mentioned in the course, this move is inferior to 13... Ng6. } 14. Ng3+
Kd7 { 14...Be7  15.Nf5  +− Wins the bishop due to the pin. } 15. b3 Nxd2 16.
Kxd2 Rd8 17. c4
{ White fixed the pawns on c5 and c6 and restricted Black's bishop on a6. After exchanging the dark squared bishops, the c5 pawn will be impossible to defend and White will simply win it with Ne4. }
17... g6 18. Bg5 { Hitting the rook on e8. White wants to play Bf6 next. }
18... Re8 19. Rxe8 Kxe8 20. Bf6
{ White attacks the rook on h8 and stops Black from developing the bishop to g7. }
20... Rg8 21. Kc3 { White is now threatening Rd1 and Rd8 checkmate. } 21... Kd7
22. Rd1+ Ke6 23. Ne4
{ White protects the bishop on f6 and is now threatening to pin the f8 bishop with Rd8. }
23... Kf5 24. f3
{ White's minor pieces are extremely active while Black's pieces are completely out of the game. The game did not last much longer. }
24... Bh6 25. Rd7 { With a double attack on the a7 and f7 pawns. } 25... Bc8
26. Rxf7 Rf8 27. g4+ Kf4 { 27...Ke6  28.Re7  is checkmate. } 28. Bg5+ Ke5 29.
Re7+ Be6 30. Bxh6
{ Black is down a piece and thus resigned.  1-0  (30)  Lomasov,S  (2540)  -Sachdev,T  (2400)  Douglas 2018 }
