[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Model games"]
[Black "1-0 Heberla,B (2580) - Gdanski,J (2474) 2017 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 e5
{ Black tries to immediately liberate his c8 bishop with 7... e5 and is even threatening ...e4. }
8. Bxc6+
{ Ruining Black's pawn structure on the queenside and winning the e5 pawn. }
8... bxc6 9. dxe5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Ng4 11. Nd2
{ White is already slightly better due to his extra pawn and superior pawn structure. }
11... Ba6 12. c4
{ An excellent move, fixing the weak pawns on c5 and c6 and restricting the bishop on a6. This was all covered in thetheoretical part of the course. }
12... Rd8 13. Kc2 Nxe5 14. b3
{ Simple and effective. The bishop on a6 is now out of the game and White will target the c5 pawn. }
14... Ng4 15. Nc3 Nxe3+ 16. fxe3 Be7 17. Rad1
{ White brings the a1 rook into the game to challenge Black's control over the d-file. }
17... O-O 18. Nf3
{ White wants to exchange all the rooks and then attack the c5 pawn. This pawn can only be defended by the bishop on e7, whilst White will be able to attack with both knights  (say with Na4 and Ne1-d3)  and win it. }
18... f6 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. Rd1 Rxd1 21. Kxd1 Bc8 22. Ne1
{ White is going to play Nd3 and Na4, after which the c5 pawn will drop. }
22... Bf5 23. e4 Bg6 24. Nd3 Bd6 25. h3 Kf7 26. Ke2
{ The king is heading to e3 to protect the e4 pawn, which will then free the c3 knight to go to a4. }
26... Ke6 27. Ke3 f5
{ Black's position was already difficult but ...f5 makes White's task even easier. }
28. Na4 fxe4 29. Naxc5+ Bxc5+ 30. Nxc5+ Ke5 { Defending the e4 pawn. } 31. Nd7+
Kd6
{ 31...Ke6  32.Nf8  Ke5  33.Nxg6  hxg6  This is a winning king and pawn endgame for White. White will create a passed-pawn on the queenside, which will distract Black's king. Then, White will take the e4 pawn and capture all of the kingside pawns. }
32. Nf8 Kc5 33. Nxg6 hxg6 34. a3 { Stopping Kb4 before capturing the e4 pawn. }
34... a5 35. Kxe4 a4 36. bxa4 Kxc4 37. h4 c5 38. a5
{ 1-0  (38)  Heberla, B  (2580)  - Gdanski, J  (2474)  Katowice 2017  Black resigned in view of   38...Kb5  39.Kd5  Kxa5  40.Kxc5  While Black's king is distracted by the pawn on a3, White's monarch will capture the pawns on the kingside. }
