[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Model games"]
[Black "1-0 Arribas Lopez,A (2505) -Abrahamyan,T (2333) 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 e5
{ As mentioned in chapter 5, this move does not equalize. } 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9.
dxe5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Ng4 11. Nd2 Nxe5 12. Re1
{ This idea behind this at first sight mysterious rook move is to meet ...Ng4 with Nf4 so that Nxe3 can be met by Rxe3. }
12... Ng4 13. Nf4 Nxe3+ 14. Rxe3+ Be7 15. Ke2 Bg4+ 16. f3
{ 16. Kf1 was arguably stronger. } 16... Bf5 17. Ne4
{ This is inaccurate. With 17. Ne4, White blocks the rook on e3. Now the Be7 is no longer under attack, allowing Black to get out of the pin with O-O-O. Much better would have been 17. Nd3, when White can continue with Re1/d1 later on with a clear advantage. }
17... O-O-O
{ Now that Be7 is no longer under attack, Black immediately takes the opportunity to castle queenside. }
18. Rd1 Rxd1
{ 18...c4  taking control over the d3 square  (stops Nd3)  , would have been a better try. }
19. Kxd1 Rd8+ 20. Ke2 Rd4
{ It's not clear what Black is trying to achieve with Rd4.  Once again   20...c4  was much better. }
21. c3 Ra4 22. a3
{ Better was   23.Ng3  hitting the e7 and f5 bishops  23...Bg5  23.Nxf5  Bxf4  24.Re8  Kb7  And only now  25.a3  ± With a much better version compared to the game  (the immediate a3 allows Black to exchange several pieces and equalize)  . }
22... Bxe4 23. Rxe4 Rxe4+ 24. fxe4 Bd6
{ Black could have immediately equalized with   24...c4  25.e5  f5  !  26.exf6  Bxf6  27.Nh5  Be5  = }
25. g3 Kd7 26. Kd3
{ White is still slightly better due to Black's compromised pawn structure on the queenside. Nevertheless, Black should be able to hold without too much trouble. }
26... g5 27. Ng2 { White wants to bring the knight to f5. } 27... h5 28. Ne3
Ke6 29. Nf5 Bf8
{ Better would have been   29...Ke5  aiming to meet  30.Ng7  with the strong  30...c4  31.Kxc4  Kxe4  Exchanging pawns favors the defender. Black is already fine and the game could continue with:  32.Nxh5  f5  33.Ng7  f4  34.Ne6  Be7  35.Nxg5  Bxg5  36.gxf4  Be7  37.b4  Kxf4  38.b5  White will exchange the queenside pawns and the game will end in a draw. }
30. h3 Ke5 31. Ne3 Ke6 32. Ke2 Bd6 33. Kf3 Bc7 34. Nf5 Kf6 35. Ke3
{ White has not managed to make any progress. } 35... Bb6
{ 35...g4  exchanging a pair of pawns, was a better try. } 36. Kd3 Ke5 37. Ng7
{ Allows Black back to exchange the weak c5 pawn for White's pawn on e4.   37.Ne3  with the idea Nc4 was much better. }
37... c4+ 38. Kxc4 Kxe4 39. Nxh5 Kf3 40. Kd3 f5 41. b4 Bc7 42. Ng7 Kxg3 43.
Nxf5+ Kxh3 44. Nd4 g4
{ Restricting the knight first with   44...Be5  45.Nxc6  Bf6  was stronger. Black would then be able to push the g-pawn all the way to g2 and draw the game. }
45. Nxc6 g3 46. Nd4 g2 47. Ne2 Kg4 48. Ke4 Bh2 49. c4 Kg5 50. Kf3 g1=Q 51. Nxg1
Bxg1 52. Ke4 Kf6 53. Kd5 Be3 54. Kc6 Ke6
{ Throws away the game. Black was probably in serious time trouble.   54...Bc1  would have lead to a draw:  55.a4  Bd2  56.b5  Ke7  57.c5  Kd8  58.Kb7  Be3  59.c6  Bb6  60.c7  Bxc7  = }
55. c5 a5 56. Kb7 axb4
{ Black resigned since White will easily create a queen with axb4, followed by b5-b6 and c6-c7.  1-0  (58)  Arribas Lopez,A  (2505)  -Abrahamyan,T  (2333)  Saint Louis 2017 }
