[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Model games"]
[Black "1-0 Kovalev,V (2641) - Tabatabaei,M (2577) 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 Nd5 8.
Bxd5 Qxd5 9. Nbc3 Qxg2 10. Rg1 Qf3
{ As mentioned in chapter 5, this move is a mistake. Much better is 10... Qxh2. }
11. Nb5 Rb8 { The only way to avoid losing a rook to Nc7+. } 12. dxc5 f6 13.
Nd6+ Bxd6 14. Qxd6
{ White is already close to winning after only 14 moves. Black's king is stuck in the center, the g7 pawn is hanging and Rd1 is coming. }
14... g6
{ Weakens the kingside considerably.   14...Rg8  would have been a better try although Black's position would still have been difficult. }
15. Rd1
{ White brings the last piece into the game. Note that O-O-O is not possible as the e2 knight would be hanging. }
15... Rf8 16. Nd4
{ This move is inaccurate as it allows Black to exchange queens with 16...Qd5.  Much better would have been   16.b4  a6  Stopping b5  17.a4  Ra8  18.Bh6  Attacking the rook on f8  Rg8  19.Qc7  +- White is threatening Qxh7 and b5, followed by Rd8 checkmate. Black is completely lost. }
16... Qd5 17. Qxd5 exd5
{ Black managed to exchange queens. Nevertheless, he is still clearly worse. }
18. Bf4 { Improving the bishop's position with a tempo on the rook on b8. }
18... Nxd4 19. Rxd4 Ra8 20. Rxd5
{ This is inaccurate and Black should be able to hold in this opposite-colored bishop endgame.    A better try would have been   20.Bd6  Rh8  21.Kd2  Clearing the way for Rg1-e1.  21...Kf7  22.Re1  With the idea Re7. Black might be able to hold with precise play, but White is clearly pushing. }
20... Be6 21. Rd6 Kf7 22. Kd2 g5 23. Be3 Rfd8 24. Rxd8 Rxd8+ 25. Kc3 Rd7
{ Is inaccurate. White's only way of winning this position is to push the queenside pawns. Black should have immediately put a stop to this plan with 25... Bd5, aiming to plant the bishop on c6 and making it very hard for White to make any progress on the queenside. }
26. a4
{ This is also inaccurate as it allows   26...a5  White should have played b4 first and only then a4, not allowing ...a5. }
26... h5
{ 26...a5!  stopping White from being able to use his queenside majority to create a passed pawn, was necessary. }
27. b4
{ Now White is already winning. There is no stopping White from creating a passed pawn on the queenside. }
27... a6 28. b5 axb5 29. axb5 Bf5 30. Ra1
{ White activates the rook and will invade Black's position with Ra8-c8, after which c6 will be decisive. }
30... Be4 31. Ra4 Bf3 32. Ra8 Rd1 33. Rc8 Ke6 34. Bd4
{ White decides to target the f6 pawn before pushing c6. The immediate c6 was also winning. }
34... Rc1 35. Kb2 Rh1 36. Rf8 f5 37. Rf6+ Kd5 38. c6 bxc6 39. b6
{ Black resigned since he cannot stop the b6 pawn from queening.   1-0  (39)  Kovalev,V  (2641)  - Tabatabaei,M  (2577)  Moscow 2018 }
