{ We are now going to look at a blitz game between GM Vladimir Kramnik with the White pieces and GM Fabiano Caruana with Black. White got a winning position after only 12 moves but then failed to find the best continuation and even ended up losing the game after blundering later on. Well, as I said, it was only a blitz game. Most importantly, the opening with 3. Bd3 was a huge success. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 Nd5 8.
Bxd5 Qxd5 9. Nbc3 Qxg2 10. Rg1 Qf3 11. Nb5 Rb8 12. dxc5
{ After only 12 moves, White is already close to winning. The opening was clearly a huge success. }
12... Bd7
{ This was all covered in chapter 5 of the course, where I mentioned that the cleanest way to win is to play 13. Qd3 followed by O-O-O. }
13. Nc7+ { This is still winning. } 13... Kd8 14. Nb5 Ne5 15. Qd4
{ This is inaccurate and allows Black to get back into the game.  Stronger was   15.Nbd4  !  15...Qh5  16.Rg5  Nf3  17.Nxf3  Qxf3  18.Qd2  Next up is 0-0-0 with a clear advantage. }
15... Qd5 16. O-O-O Qxd4
{ Exchanging queens is huge accomplishment for Black. } 17. Bxd4
{ This is a blunder as it allows Nf3 with a fork.  Much better was   17.Nexd4  when White would still have been in the driving seat. }
17... Nf3
{ Suddenly the rook on g1 and the knight on b5 are hanging. Black will pick up some material. }
18. Bxg7
{ After making one bad move, White makes an even worse one. This capture blunders the game away.   18.Nd6  was necessary although Black will still emerge up an exchange. }
18... Nxg1 19. Bxh8 Nxe2+ { Black captures the knight on e2 with check. } 20.
Kb1
{ The point is that   20.Kd2  is met by  20...Bxb5  which wins a piece and protects the knight on e2. }
20... Bxc5
{ Black is simply up a piece and went on to win the game. Since this was a blitz game, there is no point in annotating the rest of the game as both players were probably already low on time. }
21. Bf6+ Kc8 22. Nd6+ Bxd6 23. Rxd6 Nf4 24. Rd4 Ng6 25. h4 h5 26. Rc4+ Bc6 27.
Rc5 Kd7 28. Rxh5 e5 29. Rh6 Ke6 30. Bg5 Kf5 31. b3 Be4 32. Rh7 Bd5 33. c4 Be6
34. Be3 b6 35. h5 Nf4 36. h6 Kg6 37. Rg7+ Kxh6 38. Rg1 Rd8 39. Kb2 Kh5 40. a4
Rd7 41. a5 bxa5 42. Ra1 Kg4 43. Rxa5 Kf3 44. Ka3 Nd3 45. Bxa7 e4 46. c5 Rb7 47.
Bb6 Nxf2 48. Ra6 Bd5 49. c6 Bxc6 50. Bxf2 Kxf2 51. Rxc6 e3 52. Rf6+ Ke1 53. b4
e2 54. Rf5 Re7
{ 0-1  (54)  Kramnik,V  (2808)  -Caruana,F  (2808)  Altibox Norway Chess Blitz Stavanger 2017 }
