[White "8. Model games"]
[Black "1-0 Haldorsen,B (2463) -Garcia Dorado,A (2152) 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a model game in the 11. gxf3 variation that showcases how easily Black can come under a devastating attack if he does not play precisely. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 c5 6. Ne2 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Ne5 9. Nc3 a6 10. Qe2 Nxf3+ 11. gxf3 Bb4
{ 11... Qc7, as covered inchapter 7, is Black's best move. } 12. O-O-O
{ White ignores Black's Bxc3 'threat' and completes his development. White is now threatening discoveries with Nc6 and Nxe6. }
12... Qe7
{ 12...Bxc3  is a mistake  13.Nxe6  Bxb2  14.Kxb2  Qe7  The point is that now White has the beautiful  15.Nc7  that leads to checkmate  (or to winning the queen)  .  Qxc7  16.Bb6  Qe7  17.Rd8  Checkmate. Note that the queen on e7 is pinned. }
13. Ne4
{ In the 3. dxe4 chapter, I proposed the novelty 13. Nb3. This move allows Black to equalize with the e5 push. }
13... e5 14. Nb3 Nxe4 15. fxe4 O-O
{ Black castles into a vicious attack.  Better would have been   15...Be6  with a slightly worse position. }
16. Rhg1 Re8
{ I'm not exactly sure what the reason behind this move is. Rd8 seemed more natural. }
17. a3 { Kicking back Black's only active piece. } 17... Bd6 18. Qd3 Bc7 19.
Qc3 f6 20. Nc5 Kh8 21. h4
{ White is going to try to use the h-pawn to open up Black's kingside. } 21...
Bd6 { Black had to play ...h5. } 22. h5 Bxc5
{ Black gets rid of White's annoying knight. The presence of opposite colored bishops usually favors the attacking side and this is no exception. }
23. Bxc5 Qf7 24. h6
{ Now Black is going to have to compromise the king's pawn shield. } 24... g6
25. f4
{ White correctly sacrifices the f-pawn to open lines against Black's king. }
25... exf4 26. Rgf1 Kg8
{ Trying to defend the f4 pawn with   26...g5  is no good.  27.Bd4  Threatening Bxf6.  27...Re6  28.Bxf6  Exploiting the weak back rank.  28...Rxf6  29.Rd8  Qg8  30.Qxf6  is checkmate. }
27. Rxf4 Be6
{ 27...Re6  leaves the back rank irremediably weak  28.Rd8  Re8  29.Rxe8  Qxe8  30.Qxf6  Black has no defense against the mating threat of Qg7. }
28. Rxf6 Qc7 29. Rg1 { Threatening Rgxg6. } 29... Bf7 30. Rgf1 Re5
{ 30...Be6  Also fails to put any resistance.  31.Rf7  +- Black has no defense against Qg7 checkmate. }
31. Rxf7 Qxc5 32. Qxc5 Rxc5
{ Black resigned on account of Rgg7+ followed by Rff7. Black has no defense against the simple mating sequence of Rg7xh7, Rf7-g7+ and Rh8 checkmate.  For example   33.Rg7  Kh8  34.Rff7  Rac8  35.Rxh7  Kg8  36.Rfg7  Kf8  37.Rh8  is checkmate.  1-0  (32)  Haldorsen,B  (2463)  -Garcia Dorado,A  (2152)  Lisbon 2020 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Model games"]
[Black "1-0 flyingbishop97 vs. SchieberSpieler Lichess 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a 30 min rapid game played by the Chessable user flyingbishop97, who is atop the leaderboard of this course. He put all those Chessable points to good use and defeated a FM in the following game, which he annotated for the website chesstuts.com and granted me permission to include in this course.  Almost all the  (excellent)  annotations are by flyingbishop97 and I just added a few minor comments, which I denoted with CFL  (no, not the Canadian Football League but my Chessable username Chessforlife!)  . }
1. e4 { Well, what did you expect? I love me some 1. e4. } 1... e6
{ My opponent goes for the French Defense. I have mixed feelings about this opening. On the one hand, it's a strong weapon, but on the other, it just doesn't feel right, blocking in that c8-bishop. }
2. d4 d5 3. Bd3
{ My not so secret anti-French weapon. I love this line because it's rare, but also dangerous, contrary to popular belief. It also takes most french players out of their comfort zone, and into mine. }
3... dxe4
{ The main line. Black intends to follow up with...Nf6 and ...c5, opening the position and activating his pieces. Black has other alternatives, like 3...Nf6 and 3...c5. }
4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3
{ The bishop may look weird here, but it does a vital job, and is essential to making this whole system work. With the bishop on f3, White restrains the movement of the already bad c8-bishop @@StartBracket@@it can't move without dropping the b7-pawn@@EndBracket@@, and makes it so that Black will have to make quite a few preparatory moves before that c8-bishop and a8-rook ever get into the game. }
5... Nbd7
{ I would argue that this move is the best response to 3. Bd3. Chess is all about advantages, and because of the awkward placement of the bishop on f3, it's much easier for Black to grab the bishop pair, usually by ...e5 and ...Nxe5. ...Nbd7 aims to do just that. Instead of playing into White's hands with ...c5 and ...cxd4, Black aims for the very logical idea of ...e5!  @@StartBracket@@with ...Bd6@@EndBracket@@, taking advantage of the f3-bishop. }
6. Nc3
{ I would like to quote ChessForLife @@StartBracket@@the author of the Bd3 French course@@EndBracket@@ here: 'This is stronger than the more common 6. Ne2. The point is that 6. Ne2 allows Black to equalize after ...Bd6 and ...e5 @@StartBracket@@with 6. Nc3 we have the option of disrupting this plan with Nb5@@EndBracket@@.' }
6... c6
{ A very logical move. Black blocks the scope of our f3 bishop, making it look pretty silly on f3. This system with ...c6 is one of the most annoying to face as White because most of the normal plans don't work. Add this to the fact that Black has no real weaknesses, and you get just confusion and sadness as White. Black intends to complete development via ...Bd6 and ... 0-0. }
7. Nge2
{ The typical development scheme of this variation. The knight is coming to g3, and from there, e4. }
7... Bd6 8. O-O e5
{ This is quite an ambitious move. Black reasons that if he can open the center quickly, that f3 bishop can be taken advantage of much more quickly, and he will achieve equality. This pawn break also might symmetricalize @@StartBracket@@CFL: not sure that's a word but let's go with it!@@EndBracket@@ the pawn structure, leaving White to wonder where his advantage is. That being said, this move is probably a bit premature as it weakens the f5 square, and might prove to be a tad bit too hasty with the king in the center. Ideas such as Ng3-f5 and d5! are on the cards. }
9. Ng3
{ Heading for f5. White reasons that if the pawn structure will get symmetrical, his much more active pieces will grant him an advantage. }
9... O-O 10. Nf5
{ I don't want to call this move hasty, but I guess it is. Without developing my pieces, I immediately wanted to go after the bishop because I saw it's potential after a future ...e5-e4. 2 games have reached this position after 9...0-0, and both saw 10. d5, blowing open the center. If I ever got this position again, I would have still gone for Nf5, only because of its aggressive tendencies.   CLF: White's best move is  10.d5!  cxd5  11.Nxd5  followed by Bg5, Re1, and Qe2 with a slight advantage. }
10... Bc7 11. Bg5
{ I gotta develop my pieces man! At this point I wasn't feeling super good because I realized that my pieces didn't have a cohesive strategy, and they were just 'there'. }
11... h6 12. Bh4
{ 12. Bxf6 is also possible, but after ... Nxf6 all of my pieces have to retreat and black is steadily gaining an initiative.   CFL: Worse is  12.Bxf6  giving away the bishop pair. After  12...Nxf6  Black is doing very well. }
12... exd4
{ Opening up the c7-bishop, and possibly hinting at some ...Ne5 ideas. } 13.
Qxd4
{ In hindsight, this move is quite suspicious because Black is now easily able to pick up the bishop pair and leave me in a world of hurt. I feared Nxd4 Ne5 though, where Black's pieces would come to life. 13. Ne4 was an interesting idea, but I doubt it would do much good.   13.Ne4  Be5= }
13... Ne5
{ This move is the most natural, and best move. While simultaneously attacking my f3-bishop and f5-knight, Black threatens to trade queens. This was quite a bolt from the blue for me, and I'm not sure what I thought Black would have played before. I have a couple of options here, but NONE of them are good. }
14. Be4
{ I would say from a practical standpoint, this is the most human move. White keeps the pawn structure intact and accepts that he will lose the bishop pair. The engines however state that this is completely lost, and give the following line after 15...Nxe4:   14.Qxd8  Nxf3+  15.gxf3  Bxd8  This was probably the lesser of the two evils. }
14... Qxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxe4
{ Black just grabs the bishop pair.   15...g5  16.f4  gxh4  17.fxe5  Bxe5  With a better version of the game line. }
16. Nxe4 g5
{ At a first glance, with Bg3 ...f5-f4 coming, White looks lost, as my pieces will be trapped. Luckily, I found a nice resource which still kinda keeps me in the game. }
17. f4
{ This move hits both the knight on e5, and the pawn on g5. Now follows a forced sequence: }
17... gxh4 18. fxe5 Bxe5
{ I think that this is a good place to stop. Let's start with the pawn structure. White's is quite solid, although being a pawn down. Black's pawn structure is fine on the queenside, but completely wrecked on the kingside. Black is a pawn up though, and that should count for something. Next, the minor pieces. White has two very well placed knights in the center of the board which have lots of squares to jump to because of the weakened pawn structure. Black on the other hand has a powerful bishop pair, which in theory should be much, much stronger than the knights, but theory is not practice. Lastly, the rooks. White has a very active rook on f1 that could prove to be deadly, and his a1-rook is coming to d1 or e1. Black's rooks aren't active for the moment, but that could change after Rad8 and Rfe8. Overall though, Black is most definitely better here.    @@StartBracket@@CFL: that's a lot of arrows but a really nice paragraph!@@EndBracket@@ }
19. c3
{ Simple reinforcing the knight. My logic was that any other move allows Black's bishops to become freer, and the d4 knight is amazing. Why would I want to move it? }
19... f5
{ Kicking the knight away from its active post. The engine also likes this move a lot, but I will have to disagree with it. By playing f5, Black locks in his c8-bishop as now it can't move to g4, and has to instead sit on d7. This means that the a8-rook will take longer to get into the game, and I might procure an initiative.   19...h3  This seems logical to me, trying to get rid of Black's weaknesses. Black can continue with h6-h5-h4 next. }
20. Nd2
{ I like this move a lot. White prepares Nd2-f3, Nc4, and Rae1. To be honest, Black's bishops looks pretty silly on e5, as it doesn't have any targets. }
20... c5
{ Black keeps on kicking away White's pieces, but he is getting dangerously behind in development, and leaving lots of key squares weak. }
21. N4f3 Bf6 22. Nc4
{ In come the invaders! By playing ...f5 and ...c5, Black has weakened the d5 and e5 squares, both of which are amazing squares for the knights. Nc4 aims to take control of the e5-square. }
22... Be6
{ Black is getting his pieces out now, but White can start to build up an initiative with the knights. }
23. Nd6 b6 24. Rfe1
{ Note how as White is developing, he is gaining tempi simultaneously. This move also supports the e5 square, and prepares possible Ne5 ideas. }
24... Bd7 25. Ne5
{ Look at those knights! Black basically has to give up his bishop pair now. }
25... Bxe5
{ Other moves are just too passive:   25...Bc8  26.Rad1  when White has good activity. }
26. Rxe5
{ The weakness of the kingside pawns are going to be highlighted very soon. }
26... Rf6 { Are we going to move our knight? Absolutely not! } 27. Rd1 Re6
{ Black keeps trading pieces, but I don't think this benefits him. By trading more pieces, the weakness of the kingside pawns really gets more highlighted, and the more weak squares the knight can infiltrate.   27...h3  Perhaps this was better, trying to liquidate weaknesses.  28.gxh3  Material is equal, but I have doubled h-pawns. }
28. Nc4
{ Again, I target the weak e5-square and support my rook. If my knight gets to e5, it will be an octopus. }
28... Rxe5 29. Nxe5 Be6 30. a3
{ Of course! In endgames, you want to place your pawns on the opposite color of the bishop, essentially making that bishop useless with no targets. }
30... Re8
{ Black is setting up some discoveries along the e-file. Because that bishop has no targets, this 'threat' is actually not a threat at all. }
31. Kf2
{ Endgames require king activity. In hindsight though, this was a little hasty. Black now has a nice set of moves which net him an advantage.   31.Ng6  This move was better, going to f4, and remembering that 'loose pieces drop off'. }
31... h3
{ Finally this move! Me, being greedy, just snagged the material equality.   31...Bb3  32.Re1  Kg7  When a trade of rooks will most likely occur. Black's king will be more active in the resulting endgame, and white can only hope to draw. }
32. gxh3 Kg7
{ Now we get into the technical phase of the endgame. Both sides just want to improve their pieces. }
33. Kf3 Kf6 34. Kf4 Rg8 35. Nf3
{ I liked this move a lot. The knight leaves its active post, but prepares to initiate a rook trade with Rg1 @@StartBracket@@or Rd2 if ...Rg2@@EndBracket@@, after which the game will be equal.   35.Rd2  Some people after the game suggested this move, but I think that after  35...Rg1  Black is pressing and White has no active plan. }
35... Rg2 36. Rd2 Rg7
{ This makes a lot of sense. As the higher rated player, my opponent wants to keep as many chances alive as possible.   36...Rxd2  37.Nxd2  This was also possible, but Black has nothing in this equal position. If anything, only I can win because my knight can jump color complexes. }
37. Rd6
{ If I don't get ideas, he shouldn't either! By pinning the bishop, I severely limit the number of Black's possible useful moves. }
37... Ke7
{ A huge mistake. Black vacates the e5 square, and this allows me to come in. I didn't capitalize on this chance though, as I was tunnel-visioned, and had very little time.   37...Rg2  this would have been best.  38.Rd2  Rxd2  39.Nxd2  With the same endgame. }
38. Rd1
{ A howler.... The game is equal again.   38.Ke5  This would have given me an overwhelming position.  38...Bb3  39.Nh4  hitting the f5 pawn.  39...Ke8  40.Ng6  We can stop here. All of Black's pieces are scattered with no targets. }
38... Bc8 39. Rg1 Rxg1
{ Seeing nothing better, my opponent goes into the minor piece endgame. } 40.
Nxg1 Kd6
{ Now, it is just a matter of maneuvering my knight to the best spot. Black can only shuffle. }
41. Ne2 Kd5 42. b3
{ One last necessary move. Black's king cannot be allowed to penetrate into our queenside. }
42... Ke6 43. c4 { taking away d5. } 43... a6 44. Nc3
{ This is what I mean. The knight has two targets, and it will get to one of them. }
44... Bd7
{ Stopping the fatal idea of Na4. Now, I will aim to get my knight to e3, attacking f5 and preparing some queenside action. }
45. Nd5
{ CFL: better was  45.Ne2  heading to g3 to target the f5 pawn  45...b5  46.Ng3  bxc4  47.bxc4  Kf6  48.Nf1=  Black has no way of making progress. }
45... b5 46. Ne3 bxc4
{ 46...b4  this was also possible, and was probably the better move, cementing the queenside pawn structure, allowing both sides to target both sets of pawns.  47.axb4  cxb4  48.Nxf5  a5  The potential passed b-pawn can be very dangerous. }
47. Nxc4
{ Now, it is just a matter of technique. Black has too many weaknesses. } 47...
Kd5 { He had to do something. } 48. Nb6+ Ke6 49. Nxd7 Kxd7 50. Kxf5
{ This endgame, while we are a pawn up, is not completely trivial. Black has ideas of ...a5-a4 bxa4 ...c4!, winning. }
50... Kd6 51. Ke4
{ Seeing that going Kg6 didn't work, I tried the other way.   51.Kg6  This is just a draw.  51...a5  52.a4!  Stopping ...a4 ideas.  52...Kd5  53.h4  Kd4  54.Kxh6  Kc3  55.h5  Kxb3  56.Kg7  c4  57.h6  c3  58.h7  c2  59.h8=Q  c1=Q  Both sides queen, and a perpetual should be in order. }
51... a5
{ A huge mistake. This allows zugzwang when our king can come and pick up the pawns using the opposition.   51...h5  This was a much better move, and while it is still shaky, Black is still in the game.  52.h4  Kc6  53.Ke5  Kb5  54.Kd5  Kb6  55.Kd6  Kb5  56.Ke5  Kb6  57.Kf4  Kb5  58.Ke3  No side can make progress. Draw. }
52. Kd3
{ Another howler. We both had around 2 minutes here.   52.a4!  was winning. This fixes the queenside pawns, and Black's king will eventually get outmaneuvered. }
52... Kd5
{ And in turn, my opponent blunders back. I again have this idea of a4.   52...h5  Would have been better, but after  53.Kc3  Kd5  54.h4  a4  55.b4  Kc6  56.Kc4  cxb4  57.Kxb4  Kd6  58.Kxa4  Kc5  59.Ka5  Kc4  Would surprisingly be a draw. Black just barely held on! }
53. h4 h5 54. h3
{ Another one! I should have left this tempo open, and played a4! for the billionth time.   54.a4  This wins. }
54... Kd6
{ And of course, my opponent makes the last mistake, which I capitalize on. This allows me to force zugzwang. Better would have been   54...Kc6  keeping distant opposition.  55.Ke4  Kd6  56.a4  Ke6  57.Kf4  Kf6  58.Ke3  Ke5  59.Kd3  Kd6  60.Kc2  Ke5  With a draw. }
55. Kc4 a4
{ Black is just lost now.   55...Kc6  56.a4!  Is the point. Whichever way Black goes, we will take the other way. }
56. bxa4 Kc6 57. a5 Kd6 58. a6 Kc6 59. a7 Kb7 60. Kxc5 Kxa7 61. Kd5 Ka6 62. Ke5
Ka5 63. Kf5 Ka4 64. Kg5 Kxa3 65. Kxh5 Kb4 66. Kg6 Kc5 67. h5 Kd6 68. h6
{ This was a very nice win, my first over a FM in classical!   CFL: Congrats flyingbishop and thanks a lot for sending over this game with fantastic annotations! }
*

