[Black "Instructions"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ I decided to include several nice combinations I came across when going through games in the 3. Bd3 variation. Some of these tactical patterns have occurred in multiple games in this variation, i.e. they are typical motifs. A few others were just pretty so I decided to include them.  I hope you have some fun trying to solve these exercises!   Note that some of them are quite hard so don't worry if you don't find the correct solution on your first attempt. I'd recommend trying to calculate the forcing variations until the end  (and not just trying to guess the first move)  and writing down what you saw before checking the solution.  Finally, I'd recommend setting the quiz timer to infinity  (or at least a couple of minutes)  . It's 60 seconds by default because this is an opening course and Chessable does not, as of the time I'm writing this, allow for different quiz timers in different chapters. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Puzzles"]
[Black "Exercise #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "R7/p1k1r1p1/2p5/2p2Pb1/2N1p3/1P6/P1P1K1P1/8 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position occurred in the game Druska, Juraj  (2364)  - Cech, Pavel  (2467)  Prague Opocensky Memorial 2014. It came from the 3. Bd3 dxe4 7...e5 variation &#40note the weak c5 and c6 pawns typical of this variation&#41. }
1... Kb7
{ Black has just played Kb7, attacking White's rook on a8. What move did White play that won material ? }
2. Re8 Rxe8 3. Nd6+ Kc7 4. Nxe8+ Kd7 5. Nxg7
{ White won a pawn and most importantly now has two connected passed pawns on the kingside. White went on to win in 1-0  (50)  Druska,J  (2364)  -Cech,P  (2427)  Prague 2014. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Puzzles"]
[Black "Exercise #2"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rrn1k1/1p1bbppp/pq2p3/4B3/3N4/2N3RQ/PPP2PPP/1K1R4 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position resulted from the3. Bd3 dxe4 7. ..cxd4 9... Be7 variation. GM Semen Lomasov with the White pieces followed the typical plan of O-O-O and started a vicious attack on Black's king. How did he proceed? }
1. Bxg7
{ IM Li Peng with the Black pieces surely saw this coming and thought he could divert White's rook from g3 with: }
1... Rxc3 { What continuation did Black miss ? } 2. f3
{ This must have come as a surprise! White blocks the rook on c3 and is now threatening Bf6+ followed by Qh6 with checkmate.   Black was probably counting on  2.Rxc3  Nxg7∓  when he would be doing very well. }
2... Nxg7 3. Qh6 Bf8 { It looks as if Black managed to defend himself... } 4.
Nf5
{ The only move that wins! White takes advantage of the loose queen on b6. Black resigned since he has no defense against Rxg7 followed by Qxg7 checkmate. White spotted this beautiful knight move before playing Bxg7!  Note that   24.Rh3  does not win because of  24...f6  creating a square for the king on f7  25.Qxh7  Kf7  Black is actually winning now as White is down two pieces and has no more threats.  1-0 Lomasov, Semen  (2546)  vs Peng, Li Min  (2426)  Petah Tivka Winter GM 2020 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Puzzles"]
[Black "Exercise #3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/p2bbppp/4pn2/q7/1p1NN3/3RBQ2/PPP2PPP/1K1R4 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is another game from the3. Bd3 dxe4 7... cxd4 9... Be7 variation. } 1...
Nd5
{ Black has just centralized his knight with 16...Nd5. Can you find White's best move? }
2. Nf5 { A nice move, taking advantage of the loose bishop on d7. } 2... exf5
{ Black's best try.   Retreating the bishop with  17...Bd8  looses to the spectacular  18.Nh6!  18...gxh6  19.Bxh6+−  when Black is defenseless against Qg4+ followed by mate on g7.   Defending the bishop with  17...Rfe8  also runs into  18.Nh6!  18...gxh6  19.Qg3  Bg5  20.Nxg5  hxg5  21.Qxg5+−  when Black's king will be mated shortly after Bd4. }
3. Rxd5 { With a double-attack on Black's queen and rook. } 3... fxe4
{ With a counterattack on White's queen. } 4. Qh5 Qa4 5. Rxd7
{ With a clear advantage. Material is level but White's pieces are much more active. White went on to win in 1-0  (69)  Pacan Milej, K  (2301)  -Szustakowski, A  (2331)  Katowice 2018. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Puzzles"]
[Black "Exercise #4"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2b2r2/p4R1p/2p2Bpb/2p5/2P1NkP1/1PK2P2/P6P/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position arose from the 3. Bd3 dxe4 7...e5 variation &#40once again, note the weak doubled pawns on c5 and c6 characteristic of this line&#41. Black's king is surrounded by White's pieces. Can you find the move GM Semen Lomasov played in this position? }
1. Bg5+ { Double-check ! } 1... Ke5 2. Re7+ Be6 3. Bxh6
{ Black resigned since she is down a piece. 1-0  (30)  Lomasov,S  (2540)  -Sachdev,T  (2400)  Douglas 2018. If you did not recognize the initial position, take a closer look at game #4 in the model games chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Puzzles"]
[Black "Exercise #5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/1pq2ppp/p3pn2/4n3/1b1N4/2N1BB2/PPP1QPPP/2KR3R w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position came from the 3. Bd3 dxe4 7...cxd4 9...Bb4 variation. Black has just played Qc7, increasing the pressure on the knight on c3. Can you find the move White played in this position ? }
1. Ndb5 Qa5
{ The point is that  12...axb5  13.Qxb5  is not only a check but a double-attack on the Bb4 and the Kd8.  13...Nc6  14.Bxc6  Qxc6  15.Qxb4+−  White recouped the minor piece with interest. White won a pawn and Black can't even castle. White has a decisive advantage. }
2. Nd6+ Bxd6 3. Rxd6
{ White is clearly better in this position since his pieces are much more active. White's dark square bishop is going to be a monster later in the game  (note all the weak dark squares: e5, c5, d6, b6, etc)  . Black's bishop on the other hand is still stuck on c8. }
*

