[SetUp "1"]

Bb4 { Black develops the bishop to b4 with the idea to capture on c3. } 11.
O-O-O Qa5
{ Black moved the queen out of harms way and is now threatening to capture on c3. However, Black forgot the king on e8 should have castled a long time ago. How should White take advantage of this fact? }
12. Nc6
{ A stunning move! Hitting the Qa5 and threatening Rd8+ so Black is forced to capture the knight with }
12... bxc6 13. Qxc6+ Nd7 14. Qxa8
{ White is now threatening to capture the bishop on c8 so Black has not time to take on c3. }
14... O-O 15. Qxa7
{ White is an exchange and two pawns up with a completely winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Puzzles"]
[Black "Exercise #15"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pp2bppp/4pn2/8/3N4/2N1BQ2/PPP2PPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

11... Qa5
{ Black should have castled kingside but instead decided to develop the queen first. Why is this move a mistake? }
12. Nc6
{ Once again gives White an advantage. Hopefully, that was a bit easier to find after the last puzzle. Keep an eye out for this move when Black forgets about his king on e8! It has happened multiple times OTB!   The point is that  2...bxc6  3.Qxc6  wins the rook on a8. }
12... Qh5 13. Qxh5 Nxh5 14. Nxe7 Kxe7 15. g4
{ Forcing the knight back to f6 is very strong. } 15... Nf6 16. Bc5+ Ke8
{ The alternative  16...Kd7  is strongly met by  17.O-O-O  Kc6  18.g5!  Kxc5  19.gxf6  gxf6  20.Ne4+  Kb6  21.Nxf6±  White is fully developed and has a very strong knight on f6. Conversely, Black's bishop is still stuck on c8. White can continue with Rhg1-g7 with a clear edge. }
17. Nb5 { Black has no satisfactory response to the threats of Nc7+ and Nd6+. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Puzzles"]
[Black "Exercise #16"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp2bppp/4pn2/qN6/8/P1N1BQ2/1PP2PPP/2KR3R b - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14... Bd7
{ Black has just played ...Bd7 to get rid of the active knight on b5. How can White gain an advantage? }
15. Rxd7 { A very nice tactical shot! } 15... Nxd7 16. Qxb7
{ This is the point. The knight on d7 and the bishop on e7 are both loose. And as the saying goes, loose pieces drop off!. }
16... Bf6
{ This is a mistake.   Much better was  16. ..Rfd8  17.Rd1  leading to a position where after  17...Rab8  Qxa7  Qxa7  19.Bxa7  Ra8  20.a4  White is technically down an exchange, his passed pawns on the queenside coupled with the activity of his pieces actually give him the advantage. }
17. Qxd7 Rfd8 18. Qb7 Rab8
{ We have been following the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Gunnarsson, J @@StartBracket@@2450@@EndBracket@@ - Svane, R @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2017, where White missed the winning shot }
19. Qxa7 Rxb5 20. Qxa5 Rxa5 21. Bb6
{ White will get the exchange back and end up with two extra protected passed pawns. }
